# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ecology-of-banksia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] Plants with canopy seed bank store their seeds in branches, pods, and other structures of plants.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] Ecological disturbances in the ecosystem have led some plants to develop adaptive strategies such as retaining seeds and delaying the seed release.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] This ability of these plants to store seeds long-term is one of the main adaptation methods they have developed particularly against recurrent fires.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] Additionally, after disturbances, such as fire have occurred, the plant species will release the retained seeds into the ground to germinate at certain seasonal conditions that signal the appropriate time for seedling establishment.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] This process is particularly important for sustainable management and conservation of plant biodiversity.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] Maternal plants with the ability to maintain canopy seed banks actively store and protect their seeds at an elevated position within the canopy.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] This strategic placement ensures that in the event of severe disturbances such as wildfires which may result in the death of some or all adult plants, the seeds are well-positioned for dispersal, thereby preserving the genetic diversity of the species.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] The soil seed banks and seeds found on forest floors are less protected compared to the canopy seed banks, particularly during disturbances.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] In contrast, seeds stored in the canopy are protected both before and during disturbances.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] During these severe disturbances, the seed banks within the canopy are expected to be triggered and dispersed widely.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] After such disturbances, these seeds can be released into the ground, thereby serving as a reliable source for the establishment of new seedlings.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] This mechanism serves as a critical survival strategy, enabling the species to endure and regenerate following significant environmental challenges and ensure population restoration.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] Canopy seed banks are often associated with serotinous species.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] The ability of some plant species to retain seeds in protective structures and delay the release of mature seeds is known as serotiny.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] These plant species can store seeds in closed fruits or cones for days to decades until environmental changes are triggered during events such as wildfires and proper growing conditions.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] After a year or two, the widely dispersed seed starts the germination process and regeneration of species affected in the disturbed areas.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] These plant species are often found in fire-prone environments such as those of Proteaceae species in Australia, dioecious species in South Africa and pine species in the US.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] The serotiny levels of species found in specific locations are related to the fire history of those areas as fire is one the most common disturbances faced by plants.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] These plant species can retain seeds within their canopy for extended periods, eventually leading to the formation of canopy seed banks.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] Other factors aside from fire disturbances that affect the serotiny levels in plant species include the age of plants, soil quality, environmental stress and season changes in the environment.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] **Seed counting:** After collecting the seed from each cone of the sample selected, the number of seeds is counted to calculate the baseline seed density.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] **Density calculation:** The density of the canopy is calculated as the total number of seeds in the plot divided by the measured canopy area.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] **Extrapolation:** Using the data gathered from the samples collected, the seed density of the selected site can be extrapolated to estimate the seed bank size for the entire canopy.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] **Statistical analysis:** Statistical methods are used to analyse the data, compare the means, and determine the seed bank of estimates of plants.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/aerial-seed-bank] These statistical methods include t-test distribution, one-way analysis of variance (ANOVA) and regression modelling.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] As of 2021, small farms, of which the vast majority are one hectare (about 2.5 acres) or smaller, produce about one-third of the world's food.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Moreover, five of every six farms in the world consist of fewer than 2 hectares (4.9 acres) and take up only around 12% of all agricultural land.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In terms of total land use, large farms are dominant.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] While only 1% of all farms globally are greater than 50 hectares (120 acres), they encompass more than 70% of the world's farmland.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Further, nearly 40% of all global agricultural land is found on farms larger than 1,000 hectares (2,500 acres).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Farms and farming greatly influence rural economics and greatly shape rural society, affecting both the direct agricultural workforce and broader businesses that support the farms and farming populations.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The major agricultural products can be broadly grouped into foods, fibers, fuels, and raw materials (such as rubber and timber).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Food classes include cereals (grains), vegetables, fruits, cooking oils, meat, milk, eggs, and fungi.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Global agricultural production amounts to approximately 11 billion tonnes of food, 32 million tonnes of natural fibers and 4 billion m3 of wood.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] However, around 14% of the world's food is lost from production before reaching the retail level.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Modern agronomy, plant breeding, agrochemicals such as pesticides and fertilizers, and technological developments have sharply increased crop yields, but also contributed to ecological and environmental damage.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Selective breeding and modern practices in animal husbandry have similarly increased the output of meat, but have raised concerns about animal welfare and environmental damage.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Environmental issues include contributions to climate change, depletion of aquifers, deforestation, antibiotic resistance, and other agricultural pollution.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Agriculture is both a cause of and sensitive to environmental degradation, such as biodiversity loss, desertification, soil degradation, and climate change, all of which can cause decreases in crop yield.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Genetically modified organisms are widely used, although some countries ban them.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The word *agriculture* is a late Middle English adaptation of Latin *agricultūra*, from *ager* 'field' and *cultūra* 'cultivation' or 'growing'.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Agriculture is defined with varying scopes, in its broadest sense using natural resources to "produce commodities which maintain life, including food, fiber, forest products, horticultural crops, and their related services".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Thus defined, it includes arable farming, horticulture, animal husbandry and forestry, but horticulture and forestry are in practice often excluded.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] It may also be broadly decomposed into **plant agriculture**, which concerns the cultivation of useful plants, and **animal agriculture**, the production of agricultural animals.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] While agriculture usually refers to human activities, other species have been cultivating crops for up to 60 million years, such as some ant (see agriculture in ants), termite and beetle.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The development of agriculture enabled the human population to grow many times larger than could be sustained by hunting and gathering.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Agriculture began independently in different parts of the globe, and included a diverse range of taxa, in at least 11 separate centers of origin.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Wild grains were collected and eaten from at least 105,000 years ago.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In the Paleolithic Levant, 23,000 years ago, cereals cultivation of emmer, barley, and oats has been observed near the sea of Galilee.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Rice was domesticated in China between 11,500 and 6200 BC with the earliest known cultivation from 5700 BC, followed by mung, soy and azuki beans.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Sheep were domesticated in Mesopotamia between 13,000 and 11,000 years ago.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Cattle were domesticated from the wild aurochs in the areas of modern Turkey and Pakistan some 10,500 years ago.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Pig production emerged in Eurasia, including Europe, East Asia and Southwest Asia, where wild boar were first domesticated about 10,500 years ago.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In the Andes of South America, the potato was domesticated between 10,000 and 7,000 years ago, along with beans, coca, llamas, alpacas, and guinea pigs.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Sugarcane and some root vegetables were domesticated in New Guinea around 9,000 years ago.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Sorghum was domesticated in the Sahel region of Africa by 7,000 years ago.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 5,600 years ago, and was independently domesticated in Eurasia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In Mesoamerica, wild teosinte was bred into maize (corn) from 10,000 to 6,000 years ago.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The horse was domesticated in the Eurasian Steppes around 3500 BC.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Scholars have offered multiple hypotheses to explain the historical origins of agriculture.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Studies of the transition from hunter-gatherer to agricultural societies indicate an initial period of intensification and increasing sedentism; examples are the Natufian culture in the Levant, and the Early Chinese Neolithic in China.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Then, wild stands that had previously been harvested started to be planted, and gradually came to be domesticated.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In Eurasia, the Sumerians started to live in villages from about 8000 BC, relying on the Tigris and Euphrates rivers and a canal system for irrigation.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Ploughs appear in pictographs around 3000 BC; seed-ploughs around 2300 BC.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Farmers grew wheat, barley, vegetables such as lentils and onions, and fruits including dates, grapes, and figs.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Ancient Egyptian agriculture relied on the Nile River and its seasonal flooding.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Farming started in the predynastic period at the end of the Paleolithic, after 10,000 BC.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Staple food crops were grains such as wheat and barley, alongside industrial crops such as flax and papyrus.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In India, wheat, barley and jujube were domesticated by 9000 BC, soon followed by sheep and goats.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Cattle, sheep and goats were domesticated in Mehrgarh culture by 8000–6000 BC.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Cotton was cultivated by the 5th–4th millennium BC.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Archeological evidence indicates an animal-drawn plough from 2500 BC in the Indus Valley civilization.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In China, from the 5th century BC, there was a nationwide granary system and widespread silk farming.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Water-powered grain mills were in use by the 1st century BC, followed by irrigation.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] By the late 2nd century, heavy ploughs had been developed with iron ploughshares and mouldboards.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Asian rice was domesticated 8,200–13,500 years ago – depending on the molecular clock estimate that is used– on the Pearl River in southern China with a single genetic origin from the wild rice *Oryza rufipogon*.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In Greece and Rome, the major cereals were wheat, emmer, and barley, alongside vegetables including peas, beans, and olives.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Sheep and goats were kept mainly for dairy products.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In the Americas, crops domesticated in Mesoamerica (apart from teosinte) include squash, beans, and cacao.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Cocoa was domesticated by the Mayo Chinchipe of the upper Amazon around 3000 BC.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The turkey was probably domesticated in Mexico or the American Southwest.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The Aztecs developed irrigation systems, formed terraced hillsides, fertilized their soil, and developed chinampas or artificial islands.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The Mayas used extensive canal and raised field systems to farm swampland from 400 BC.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In South America agriculture may have begun about 9000 BC with the domestication of squash (Cucurbita) and other plants.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Coca was domesticated in the Andes, as were the peanut, tomato, tobacco, and pineapple.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 3600 BC.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Animals including llamas, alpacas, and guinea pigs were domesticated there.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In North America, the indigenous people of the East domesticated crops such as sunflower, tobacco, squash and *Chenopodium*.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Wild foods including wild rice and maple sugar were harvested.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The domesticated strawberry is a hybrid of a Chilean and a North American species, developed by breeding in Europe and North America.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The indigenous people of the Southwest and the Pacific Northwest practiced forest gardening and fire-stick farming.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The natives controlled fire on a regional scale to create a low-intensity fire ecology that sustained a low-density agriculture in loose rotation; a sort of "wild" permaculture.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] A system of companion planting called the Three Sisters was developed in North America.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The three crops were winter squash, maize, and climbing beans.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Indigenous Australians, long supposed to have been nomadic hunter-gatherers, practiced systematic burning, possibly to enhance natural productivity in fire-stick farming.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Scholars have pointed out that hunter-gatherers need a productive environment to support gathering without cultivation.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Because the forests of New Guinea have few food plants, early humans may have used "selective burning" to increase the productivity of the wild karuka fruit trees to support the hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The Gunditjmara and other groups developed eel farming and fish trapping systems from some 5,000 years ago.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] There is evidence of 'intensification' across the whole continent over that period.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In two regions of Australia, the central west coast and eastern central, early farmers cultivated yams, native millet, and bush onions, possibly in permanent settlements.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In the Middle Ages, compared to the Roman period, agriculture in Western Europe became more focused on self-sufficiency.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The agricultural population under feudalism was typically organized into manors consisting of several hundred or more acres of land presided over by a lord of the manor with a Roman Catholic church and priest.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Thanks to the exchange with the Al-Andalus where the Arab Agricultural Revolution was underway, European agriculture transformed, with improved techniques and the diffusion of crop plants, including the introduction of sugar, rice, cotton and fruit trees (such as the orange).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] After 1492, the Columbian exchange brought New World crops such as maize, potatoes, tomatoes, sweet potatoes, and manioc to Europe, and Old World crops such as wheat, barley, rice, and turnips, and livestock (including horses, cattle, sheep and goats) to the Americas.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Irrigation, crop rotation, and fertilizers advanced from the 17th century with the British Agricultural Revolution, allowing global population to rise significantly.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Since 1900, agriculture in developed nations, and to a lesser extent in the developing world, has seen large rises in productivity as mechanization replaces human labor, and assisted by synthetic fertilizers, pesticides, and selective breeding.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The Haber-Bosch method allowed the synthesis of ammonium nitrate fertilizer on an industrial scale, greatly increasing crop yields and sustaining a further increase in global population.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Pastoralism involves managing domesticated animals.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In nomadic pastoralism, herds of livestock are moved from place to place in search of pasture, fodder, and water.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] This type of farming is practiced in arid and semi-arid regions of Sahara, Central Asia and some parts of India.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In shifting cultivation, a small area of forest is cleared by cutting and burning the trees.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The cleared land is used for growing crops for a few years until the soil becomes too infertile, and the area is abandoned.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Another patch of land is selected and the process is repeated.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] This type of farming is practiced mainly in areas with abundant rainfall where the forest regenerates quickly.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] This practice is used in Northeast India, Southeast Asia, and the Amazon Basin.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Subsistence farming is practiced to satisfy family or local needs alone, with little left over for transport elsewhere.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] It is intensively practiced in Monsoon Asia and South-East Asia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] An estimated 2.5 billion subsistence farmers worked in 2018, cultivating about 60% of the earth's arable land.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Intensive farming is cultivation to maximize productivity, with a low fallow ratio and a high use of inputs (water, fertilizer, pesticide and automation).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] It is practiced mainly in developed countries.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] From the twentieth century onwards, intensive agriculture increased crop productivity.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] It substituted synthetic fertilizers and pesticides for labor, but caused increased water pollution, and often involved farm subsidies.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Soil degradation and diseases such as stem rust are major concerns globally; approximately 40% of the world's agricultural land is seriously degraded.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Modern agriculture has raised or encountered ecological, political, and economic issues including water pollution, biofuels, genetically modified organisms, tariffs and farm subsidies, leading to alternative approaches such as the organic movement.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Unsustainable farming practices in North America led to the Dust Bowl of the 1930s.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In recent years there has been a backlash against the environmental effects of conventional agriculture, resulting in the organic, regenerative, and sustainable agriculture movements.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] One of the major forces behind this movement has been the European Union, which first certified organic food in 1991 and began reform of its Common Agricultural Policy (CAP) in 2005 to phase out commodity-linked farm subsidies, also known as decoupling.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The growth of organic farming has renewed research in alternative technologies such as integrated pest management, selective breeding, and controlled-environment agriculture.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] There are concerns about the lower yield associated with organic farming and its impact on global food security.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Recent mainstream technological developments include genetically modified food.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] During the 60-year period between 1964 and 2023, most of the increase in agricultural production was achieved through intensification, while the expansion of agricultural land was limited to just 8%.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In the twenty-first century, between 2001 and 2023, global agricultural area decreased by 78 million hectares (Mha) (−2%), with cropland area increasing by 78 Mha and permanent meadows and pastures decreasing by 151 Mha.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] These changes exhibit significant regional variations.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa witnessed cropland expansion of 69 Mha accompanied by 72 Mha of forest loss, while Latin America saw 25 Mha of cropland growth alongside 85 Mha of net forest area loss.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Agricultural expansion remains the primary driver of global deforestation, accounting for nearly 90% of forest loss.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In this century, another important aspect to consider is that approximately 3.6 Mha of croplands are abandoned annually, with land degradation likely playing a significant role in these losses.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] By 2015, the agricultural output of China was the largest in the world, followed by the European Union, India and the United States.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Economists measure the total factor productivity of agriculture, according to which agriculture in the United States is roughly 1.7 times more productive than it was in 1948.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Agriculture employed 873 million people in 2021, or 27% of the global workforce, 916 million in 2023, compared with 1 027 million (or 40%) in 2000.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The share of agriculture in global GDP was stable at around 4% since 2000–2023.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Despite increases in agricultural production and productivity, between 702 and 828 million people were affected by hunger in 2021.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Food insecurity and malnutrition can be the result of conflict, climate extremes and variability and economic swings.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] It can also be caused by a country's structural characteristics such as income status and natural resource endowments as well as its political economy.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Pesticide use in agriculture went up 62% between 2000 and 2021, with the Americas accounting for half the use in 2021.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The International Fund for Agricultural Development posits that an increase in smallholder agriculture may be part of the solution to concerns about food prices and overall food security, given the favorable experience of Vietnam.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Agriculture provides about one-quarter of all global employment, more than half in sub-Saharan Africa and almost 60 percent in low-income countries.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] As countries develop, other jobs have historically pulled workers away from agriculture, and labor-saving innovations increase agricultural productivity by reducing labor requirements per unit of output.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Over time, a combination of labor supply and labor demand trends have driven down the share of population employed in agriculture.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] During the 16th century in Europe, between 55 and 75% of the population was engaged in agriculture; by the 19th century, this had dropped to between 35 and 65%.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In the same countries today, the figure is less than 10%.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] At the start of the 21st century, some one billion people, or over 1/3 of the available work force, were employed in agriculture.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] This constitutes approximately 70% of the global employment of children, and in many countries constitutes the largest percentage of women of any industry.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The service sector overtook the agricultural sector as the largest global employer in 2007.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In many developed countries, immigrants help fill labor shortages in high-value agriculture activities that are difficult to mechanize.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Foreign farm workers from mostly Eastern Europe, North Africa and South Asia constituted around one-third of the salaried agricultural workforce in Spain, Italy, Greece and Portugal in 2013.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Around the world, women make up a large share of the population employed in agriculture.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] This share is growing in all developing regions except East and Southeast Asia where women already make up about 50 percent of the agricultural workforce.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Women make up 47 percent of the agricultural workforce in sub-Saharan Africa, a rate that has not changed significantly in the past few decades.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Women who work in agricultural production tend to do so under highly unfavorable conditions.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] They tend to be concentrated in the poorest countries, where alternative livelihoods are not available, and they maintain the intensity of their work in conditions of climate-induced weather shocks and in situations of conflict.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Women are less likely to participate as entrepreneurs and independent farmers and are engaged in the production of less lucrative crops.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The gender gap in land productivity between female- and male managed farms of the same size is 24 percent.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] On average, women earn 18.4 percent less than men in wage employment in agriculture; this means that women receive 82 cents for every dollar earned by men.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Progress has been slow in closing gaps in women's access to irrigation and in ownership of livestock, too.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Women in agriculture still have significantly less access than men to inputs, including improved seeds, fertilizers and mechanized equipment.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] On a positive note, the gender gap in access to mobile internet in low- and middle-income countries fell from 25 percent to 16 percent between 2017 and 2021, and the gender gap in access to bank accounts narrowed from 9 to 6 percentage points.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Women are as likely as men to adopt new technologies when the necessary enabling factors are put in place and they have equal access to complementary resources.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Agriculture, specifically farming, remains a hazardous industry, and farmers worldwide remain at high risk of work-related injuries, lung disease, noise-induced hearing loss, skin diseases, as well as certain cancers related to chemical use and prolonged sun exposure.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] On industrialized farms, injuries frequently involve the use of agricultural machinery, and a common cause of fatal agricultural injuries in developed countries is tractor rollovers.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Pesticides and other chemicals used in farming can be hazardous to worker health, and workers exposed to pesticides may experience illness or have children with birth defects.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] As an industry in which families commonly share in work and live on the farm itself, entire families can be at risk for injuries, illness, and death.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Ages 0–6 may be an especially vulnerable population in agriculture; common causes of fatal injuries among young farm workers include drowning, machinery and motor accidents, including with all-terrain vehicles.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Occupational fatality data from the last decade indicate that, when looking at all industries, agriculture had the leading number of work-related deaths for youth.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Within this industry, youth between the ages of 10 and 15 suffered the most non-fatal work-related injuries.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] While farming is hazardous, studies have looked at the fact that there are also many benefits to growing up and living on a farm.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The International Labor Organization considers agriculture "one of the most hazardous of all economic sectors".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] It estimates that the annual work-related death toll among agricultural employees is at least 170,000, twice the average rate of other jobs.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In addition, incidences of death, injury and illness related to agricultural activities often go unreported.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The organization has developed the Safety and Health in Agriculture Convention, 2001, which covers the range of risks in the agriculture occupation, the prevention of these risks and the role that individuals and organizations engaged in agriculture should play.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In the United States, agriculture has been identified by the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health as a priority industry sector in the National Occupational Research Agenda to identify and provide intervention strategies for occupational health and safety issues.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In the European Union, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work has issued guidelines on implementing health and safety directives in agriculture, livestock farming, horticulture, and forestry.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The Agricultural Safety and Health Council of America (ASHCA) also holds a yearly summit to discuss safety.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Extending over 4.8 billion ha in 2025 – the equivalent of one-third of the Earth's land surface – agriculture has a greater impact on land and water resources compared with any other economic sector.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Pressure on land, soil and water resources has seriously compromised the performance and future prospects of agriculture, resulting in further loss of productive land and reduced water availability for farming and other forms of agricultural production.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Agricultural expansion drives deforestation and is one of the primary causes of the degradation of carbon-rich ecosystems such as peatlands.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] An estimated 64% of agricultural land is at risk of pesticide pollution, which damages biodiversity by destroying pollinators, harms soil microbiota and makes agrifood systems less resilient to pests, pathogens and climate change.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Accounting for 72% of global freshwater withdrawals, a figure predicted to rise further in the future, agriculture contributes to and is increasingly affected by water scarcity.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Overexploitation of groundwater and seawater intrusion in coastal aquifers is widespread, with major implications for food security.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Overall production varies by country as listed.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Cropping systems vary among farms depending on the available resources and constraints; geography and climate of the farm; government policy; economic, social and political pressures; and the philosophy and culture of the farmer.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Shifting cultivation (or slash and burn) is a system in which forests are burnt, releasing nutrients to support cultivation of annual and then perennial crops for a period of several years.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Then the plot is left fallow to regrow forest, and the farmer moves to a new plot, returning after many more years (10–20).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] This fallow period is shortened if population density grows, requiring the input of nutrients (fertilizer or manure) and some manual pest control.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Annual cultivation is the next phase of intensity in which there is no fallow period.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] This requires even greater nutrient and pest control inputs.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Further industrialization led to the use of monocultures, when one cultivar is planted on a large acreage.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Because of the low biodiversity, nutrient use is uniform and pests tend to build up, necessitating the greater use of pesticides and fertilizers.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Multiple cropping, in which several crops are grown sequentially in one year, and intercropping, when several crops are grown at the same time, are other kinds of annual cropping systems known as polycultures.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In subtropical and arid environments, the timing and extent of agriculture may be limited by rainfall, either not allowing multiple annual crops in a year, or requiring irrigation.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In all of these environments perennial crops are grown (coffee, chocolate) and systems are practiced such as agroforestry.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In temperate environments, where ecosystems were predominantly grassland or prairie, highly productive annual farming is the dominant agricultural system.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Important categories of food crops include cereals, legumes, forage, fruits and vegetables.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Natural fibers include cotton, wool, hemp, silk and flax.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Specific crops are cultivated in distinct growing regions throughout the world.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Production is listed in millions of metric tons, based on FAO estimates.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Animal husbandry is the breeding and raising of animals for meat, milk, eggs, or wool, and for work and transport.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Working animals, including horses, mules, oxen, water buffalo, camels, llamas, alpacas, donkeys, and dogs, have for centuries been used to help cultivate fields, harvest crops, wrangle other animals, and transport farm products to buyers.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Livestock production systems can be defined based on feed source, as grassland-based, mixed, and landless.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] As of 2010, 30% of Earth's ice- and water-free area was used for producing livestock, with the sector employing approximately 1.3 billion people.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Between the 1960s and the 2000s, there was a significant increase in livestock production, both by numbers and by carcass weight, especially among beef, pigs and chickens, the latter of which had production increased by almost a factor of 10.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Non-meat animals, such as milk cows and egg-producing chickens, also showed significant production increases.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Global cattle, sheep and goat populations are expected to continue to increase sharply through 2050.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Aquaculture or fish farming, the production of fish for human consumption in confined operations, is one of the fastest growing sectors of food production, growing at an average of 9% a year between 1975 and 2007.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] During the second half of the 20th century, producers using selective breeding focused on creating livestock breeds and crossbreeds that increased production, while mostly disregarding the need to preserve genetic diversity.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] This trend has led to a significant decrease in genetic diversity and resources among livestock breeds, leading to a corresponding decrease in disease resistance and local adaptations previously found among traditional breeds.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Grassland based livestock production relies upon plant material such as shrubland, rangeland, and pastures for feeding ruminant animals.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Outside nutrient inputs may be used, however manure is returned directly to the grassland as a major nutrient source.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] This system is particularly important in areas where crop production is not feasible because of climate or soil, representing 30–40 million pastoralists.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Mixed production systems use grassland, fodder crops and grain feed crops as feed for ruminant and monogastric (one stomach; mainly chickens and pigs) livestock.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Manure is typically recycled in mixed systems as a fertilizer for crops.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Landless systems rely upon feed from outside the farm, representing the de-linking of crop and livestock production found more prevalently in Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development member countries.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Synthetic fertilizers are more heavily relied upon for crop production and manure use becomes a challenge as well as a source for pollution.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Industrialized countries use these operations to produce much of the global supplies of poultry and pork.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Scientists estimate that 75% of the growth in livestock production between 2003 and 2030 will be in confined animal feeding operations, sometimes called factory farming.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Much of this growth is happening in developing countries in Asia, with much smaller amounts of growth in Africa.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Some of the practices used in commercial livestock production, including the usage of growth hormones, are controversial.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Tillage is the practice of breaking up the soil with tools such as the plow or harrow to prepare for planting, for nutrient incorporation, or for pest control.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Tillage varies in intensity from conventional to no-till.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] It can improve productivity by warming the soil, incorporating fertilizer and controlling weeds, but also renders soil more prone to erosion, triggers the decomposition of organic matter releasing CO2, and reduces the abundance and diversity of soil organisms.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Pest control includes the management of weeds, insects, mites, and diseases.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Chemical (pesticides), biological (biocontrol), mechanical (tillage), and cultural practices are used.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Cultural practices include crop rotation, culling, cover crops, intercropping, composting, avoidance, and resistance.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Integrated pest management attempts to use all of these methods to keep pest populations below the number which would cause economic loss, and recommends pesticides as a last resort.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Nutrient management includes both the source of nutrient inputs for crop and livestock production, and the method of use of manure produced by livestock.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Nutrient inputs can be chemical inorganic fertilizers, manure, green manure, compost and minerals.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Crop nutrient use may also be managed using cultural techniques such as crop rotation or a fallow period.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Manure is used either by holding livestock where the feed crop is growing, such as in managed intensive rotational grazing, or by spreading either dry or liquid formulations of manure on cropland or pastures.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Water management is needed where rainfall is insufficient or variable, which occurs to some degree in most regions of the world.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Some farmers use irrigation to supplement rainfall.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In other areas such as the Great Plains in the US and Canada, farmers use a fallow year to conserve soil moisture for the following year.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Recent technological innovations in precision agriculture allow for water status monitoring and automate water usage, leading to more efficient management.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Agriculture represents 70% of freshwater use worldwide.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] However, water withdrawal ratios for agriculture vary significantly by income level.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In least developed countries and landlocked developing countries, water withdrawal ratios for agriculture are as high as 90 percent of total water withdrawals and about 60 percent in Small Island Developing States.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] According to 2014 report by the International Food Policy Research Institute, agricultural technologies will have the greatest impact on food production if adopted in combination with each other.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Payment for ecosystem services is a method of providing additional incentives to encourage farmers to conserve some aspects of the environment.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Measures might include paying for reforestation upstream of a city, to improve the supply of fresh water.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Different definitions exist for agricultural automation and for the variety of tools and technologies that are used to automate production.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] One view is that agricultural automation refers to autonomous navigation by robots without human intervention.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Alternatively, it is defined as the accomplishment of production tasks through mobile, autonomous, decision-making, mechatronic devices.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] However, FAO finds that these definitions do not capture all the aspects and forms of automation, such as robotic milking machines that are static, most motorized machinery that automates the performing of agricultural operations, and digital tools (e.g., sensors) that automate only diagnosis.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] FAO defines agricultural automation as the use of machinery and equipment in agricultural operations to improve their diagnosis, decision-making or performing, reducing the drudgery of agricultural work or improving the timeliness, and potentially the precision, of agricultural operations.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has involved a progressive move from manual tools to animal traction, to motorized mechanization, to digital equipment and finally, to robotics with artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Precision agriculture often employs such automation technologies.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Motorized machines are increasingly complemented, or even superseded, by new digital equipment that automates diagnosis and decision-making.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] A conventional tractor, for example, can be converted into an automated vehicle allowing it to sow a field autonomously.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Motorized mechanization has increased significantly across the world in recent years, although reliable global data with broad country coverage exist only for tractors and only up to 2009.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Global automatic milking system sales have increased over recent years, but adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Measuring the overall employment impacts of agricultural automation is difficult because it requires large amounts of data tracking all the transformations and the associated reallocation of workers both upstream and downstream.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] While automation technologies reduce labor needs for the newly automated tasks, they also generate new labor demand for other tasks, such as equipment maintenance and operation.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Agricultural automation can also stimulate employment by allowing producers to expand production and by creating other agrifood systems jobs.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] This is especially true when it happens in context of rising scarcity of rural labor, as is the case in high-income countries and many middle-income countries.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] On the other hand, if forcedly promoted, for example through government subsidies in contexts of abundant rural labor, it can lead to labor displacement and falling or stagnant wages, particularly affecting poor and low-skilled workers.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Climate change and agriculture are interrelated on a global scale.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Global warming is already affecting agriculture, with effects unevenly distributed across the world.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In a 2022 report, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change describes how human-induced warming has slowed growth of agricultural productivity over the past 50 years in mid and low latitudes.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Methane emissions have negatively impacted crop yields by increasing temperatures and surface ozone concentrations.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Warming is also negatively affecting crop and grassland quality and harvest stability.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Ocean warming has decreased sustainable yields of some wild fish populations while ocean acidification and warming have already affected farmed aquatic species.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Climate change will probably increase the risk of food insecurity for some vulnerable groups, such as the poor.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In order to meet the demands of a growing global population, agriculture needs to produce about 50% more food, feed and fibre by 2050 compared with the volumes it generated in 2012, according to estimates by the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Achieving such objectives will place additional pressure on the world's already overstretched water, land and soil resources.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Crop alteration has been practiced by humankind for thousands of years, since the beginning of civilization.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Altering crops through breeding practices changes the genetic make-up of a plant to develop crops with more beneficial characteristics for humans, for example, larger fruits or seeds, drought-tolerance, or resistance to pests.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Significant advances in plant breeding ensued after the work of geneticist Gregor Mendel.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] His work on dominant and recessive alleles, although initially largely ignored for almost 50 years, gave plant breeders a better understanding of genetics and breeding techniques.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Crop breeding includes techniques such as plant selection with desirable traits, self-pollination and cross-pollination, and molecular techniques that genetically modify the organism.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Domestication of plants has, over the centuries increased yield, improved disease resistance and drought tolerance, eased harvest and improved the taste and nutritional value of crop plants.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Careful selection and breeding have had enormous effects on the characteristics of crop plants.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Plant selection and breeding in the 1920s and 1930s improved pasture (grasses and clover) in New Zealand.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Extensive X-ray and ultraviolet induced mutagenesis efforts (i.e. primitive genetic engineering) during the 1950s produced the modern commercial varieties of grains such as wheat, corn (maize) and barley.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The Green Revolution popularized the use of conventional hybridization to sharply increase yield by creating "high-yielding varieties".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] For example, average yields of corn (maize) in the US have increased from around 2.5 tons per hectare (t/ha) (40 bushels per acre) in 1900 to about 9.4 t/ha (150 bushels per acre) in 2001.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Similarly, worldwide average wheat yields have increased from less than 1 t/ha in 1900 to more than 2.5 t/ha in 1990.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] South American average wheat yields are around 2 t/ha, African under 1 t/ha, and Egypt and Arabia up to 3.5 to 4 t/ha with irrigation.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In contrast, the average wheat yield in countries such as France is over 8 t/ha.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Variations in yields are due mainly to variation in climate, genetics, and the level of intensive farming techniques (use of fertilizers, chemical pest control, and growth control to avoid lodging).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Investments into innovation for agriculture are long term.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] This is because it takes time for research to become commercialized and for technology to be adapted to meet multiple regions' needs, as well as meet national guidelines before being adopted and planted in a farmer's fields.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] For instance, it took at least 60 years from the introduction of hybrid corn technology before its adoption became widespread.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Agricultural innovation developed for the specific agroecological conditions of one region is not easily transferred and used in another region with different agroecological conditions.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Instead, the innovation would have to be adapted to the specific conditions of that other region and respect its biodiversity and environmental requirements and guidelines.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Some such adaptations can be seen through the steadily increasing number of plant varieties protected under the plant variety protection instrument administered by the International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants (UPOV).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Genetically modified organisms (GMO) are organisms whose genetic material has been altered by genetic engineering techniques generally known as recombinant DNA technology.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Genetic engineering has expanded the genes available to breeders to use in creating desired germlines for new crops.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Increased durability, nutritional content, insect and virus resistance and herbicide tolerance are a few of the attributes bred into crops through genetic engineering.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] For some, GMO crops cause food safety and food labeling concerns.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Numerous countries have placed restrictions on the production, import or use of GMO foods and crops.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] The Biosafety Protocol, an international treaty, regulates the trade of GMOs.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] There is ongoing discussion regarding the labeling of foods made from GMOs, and the EU has had GMO food labeling requirements since 1997.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] As of 2022, the United States requires food containing GMO ingredients to be labeled as well.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Herbicide-resistant seeds have a gene implanted into their genome that allows the plants to tolerate exposure to herbicides, including glyphosate.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] These seeds allow the farmer to grow a crop that can be sprayed with herbicides to control weeds without harming the resistant crop.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Herbicide-tolerant crops are used by farmers worldwide.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] With the increasing use of herbicide-tolerant crops, comes an increase in the use of glyphosate-based herbicide sprays.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In some areas glyphosate resistant weeds have developed, causing farmers to switch to other herbicides.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Some studies also link widespread glyphosate usage to iron deficiencies in some crops, which is both a crop production and a nutritional quality concern, with potential economic and health implications.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Other GMO crops used by growers include insect-resistant crops, which have a gene from the soil bacterium *Bacillus thuringiensis* (Bt), which produces a toxin specific to insects.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] Some believe that similar or better pest-resistance traits can be acquired through traditional breeding practices, and resistance to various pests can be gained through hybridization or cross-pollination with wild species.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p01] In some cases, wild species are the primary source of resistance traits; some tomato cultivars that have gained resistance to at least 19 diseases did so through crossing with wild populations of tomatoes.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is both a cause of environmental degradation and sensitive to environmental degradation, such as biodiversity loss, desertification, soil degradation and climate change, which cause decreases in crop yield.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is one of the most important drivers of environmental pressures, particularly habitat change, climate change, water use and toxic emissions.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is the main source of toxins released into the environment, including insecticides, especially those used on cotton.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] The 2011 UNEP Green Economy report stated that agricultural operations produced some 13 percent of anthropogenic global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] This includes gases from the use of inorganic fertilizers, agro-chemical pesticides, and herbicides, as well as fossil fuel-energy inputs.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Agriculture imposes multiple external costs upon society through effects such as pesticide damage to nature (especially herbicides and insecticides), nutrient runoff, excessive water usage, and loss of natural environment.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] A 2000 assessment of agriculture in the UK determined total external costs for 1996 of £2,343 million, or £208 per hectare.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] A 2005 analysis of these costs in the US concluded that cropland imposes approximately $5 to $16 billion ($30 to $96 per hectare), while livestock production imposes $714 million.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Both studies, which focused solely on the fiscal impacts, concluded that more should be done to internalize external costs.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Neither included subsidies in their analysis, but they noted that subsidies also influence the cost of agriculture to society.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Agriculture seeks to increase yield and to reduce costs, often employing measures that cut biodiversity to very low levels.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Yield increases with inputs such as fertilizers and removal of pathogens, predators, and competitors (such as weeds).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Costs decrease with increasing scale of farm units, such as making fields larger; this means removing hedges, ditches and other areas of habitat.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Pesticides kill insects, plants and fungi.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Effective yields fall with on-farm losses, which may be caused by poor production practices during harvesting, handling, and storage.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] The environmental effects of climate change show that research on pests and diseases that do not generally afflict areas is essential.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] In 2021, farmers discovered stem rust on wheat in the Champagne area of France, a disease that had previously only occurred in Morocco for 20 to 30 years.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Because of climate change, insects that used to die off over the winter are now alive and multiplying.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] A senior UN official, Henning Steinfeld, said that "Livestock are one of the most significant contributors to today's most serious environmental problems".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Livestock production occupies 70% of all land used for agriculture, or 30% of the land surface of the planet.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] It is one of the largest sources of greenhouse gases, responsible for 18% of the world's greenhouse gas emissions as measured in CO2 equivalents.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] By comparison, all transportation emits 13.5% of the CO2.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] (This comparison later turned out to be an apples-and-oranges analogy.) It produces 65% of human-related nitrous oxide (which has 296 times the global warming potential of CO2) and 37% of all human-induced methane (which is 23 times as warming as CO2.) It also generates 64% of the ammonia emission.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Livestock expansion is cited as a key factor driving deforestation; in the Amazon basin 70% of previously forested area is now occupied by pastures and the remainder used for feed crops.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Through deforestation and land degradation, livestock is also driving reductions in biodiversity.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] A well documented phenomenon is woody plant encroachment, caused by overgrazing in rangelands.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Land transformation, the use of land to yield goods and services, is the most substantial way humans alter the Earth's ecosystems, and is the driving force causing biodiversity loss.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Estimates of the amount of land transformed by humans vary from 39 to 50%.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] It is estimated that 24% of land globally experiences land degradation, a long-term decline in ecosystem function and productivity, with cropland being disproportionately affected.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Land management is the driving factor behind degradation; 1.5 billion people rely upon the degrading land.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Degradation can be through deforestation, desertification, soil erosion, mineral depletion, acidification, or salinization.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] In 2021, the global agricultural land area was 4.79 billion hectares (ha), down 2 percent, or 0.09 billion ha compared with 2000.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Between 2000 and 2021, roughly two-thirds of agricultural land were used for permanent meadows and pastures (3.21 billion ha in 2021), which declined by 5 percent (0.17 billion ha).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] One-third of the total agricultural land was cropland (1.58 billion ha in 2021), which increased by 6 percent (0.09 billion ha).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Within the U.S., total agricultural land use is estimated to be 56%, and including grazing, animal agriculture constitutes around 80% of agricultural land.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Eutrophication, excessive nutrient enrichment in aquatic ecosystems resulting in algal blooms and anoxia, leads to fish kills, loss of biodiversity, and renders water unfit for drinking and other industrial uses.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Excessive fertilization and manure application to cropland, as well as high livestock stocking densities cause nutrient (mainly nitrogen and phosphorus) runoff and leaching from agricultural land.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] These nutrients are major nonpoint pollutants contributing to eutrophication of aquatic ecosystems and pollution of groundwater, with harmful effects on human populations.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Fertilizers also reduce terrestrial biodiversity by increasing competition for light, favoring those species that are able to benefit from the added nutrients.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Agriculture simultaneously is facing growing freshwater demand and precipitation anomalies (droughts, floods, and extreme rainfall and weather events) on rainfed areas fields and grazing lands.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Agriculture accounts for 70 percent of withdrawals of freshwater resources, and an estimated 41 percent of current global irrigation water use occurs at the expense of environmental flow requirements.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Within the U.S., agriculture accounts for about 80% of total water consumption, with animal agriculture making up half of agricultural consumption (around 40%).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] It is long known that aquifers in areas as diverse as northern China, the Upper Ganges and the western US are being depleted, and new research extends these problems to aquifers in Iran, Mexico and Saudi Arabia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Increasing pressure is being placed on water resources by industry and urban areas, meaning that water scarcity is increasing and agriculture is facing the challenge of producing more food for the world's growing population with reduced water resources.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] While industrial withdrawals have declined in the past few decades and municipal withdrawals have increased only marginally since 2010, agricultural withdrawals have continued to grow at an ever faster pace.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Agricultural water usage can also cause major environmental problems, including the destruction of natural wetlands, the spread of water-borne diseases, and land degradation through salinization and waterlogging, when irrigation is performed incorrectly.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Pesticide use has increased since 1950 to 2.5 million short tons annually worldwide, yet crop loss from pests has remained relatively constant.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] The World Health Organization estimated in 1992 that three million pesticide poisonings occur annually, causing 220,000 deaths.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Pesticides select for pesticide resistance in the pest population, leading to a condition termed the "pesticide treadmill" in which pest resistance warrants the development of a new pesticide.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] An alternative argument is that the way to "save the environment" and prevent famine is by using pesticides and intensive high yield farming, a view exemplified by a quote heading the Center for Global Food Issues website: 'Growing more per acre leaves more land for nature'.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] However, critics argue that a trade-off between the environment and a need for food is not inevitable, and that pesticides can replace good agronomic practices such as crop rotation.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] The Push–pull agricultural pest management technique involves intercropping, using plant aromas to repel pests from crops (push) and to lure them to a place from which they can then be removed (pull).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Agriculture contributes towards climate change through greenhouse gas emissions and by the conversion of non-agricultural land such as forests into agricultural land.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] The agriculture, forestry and land use sector contribute between 13% and 21% of global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Emissions of nitrous oxide, methane make up over half of total greenhouse gas emission from agriculture.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Animal husbandry is a major source of greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Approximately 57% of global GHG emissions from the production of food are from the production of animal-based food while plant-based foods contribute 29% and the remaining 14% is for other utilizations.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Farmland management and land-use change represented major shares of total emissions (38% and 29%, respectively), whereas rice and beef were the largest contributing plant- and animal-based commodities (12% and 25%, respectively).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] South and Southeast Asia and South America were the largest emitters of production-based GHGs.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Climate change put significant part of crops in danger already at 1.5 degrees of warming.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] While in North America, Europe and central Asia the share of endangered crops is relatively little at this level of warming, in the Middle east and North Africa region for example, close to 50% of cropland is in danger.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] With further temperature rise the risk increase in all regions, in some more, in some less.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Globally the cropland area in safe climatic zone decrease for all the major crop groups as warming exceed 1.5 degrees.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Current farming methods have resulted in over-stretched water resources, high levels of erosion and reduced soil fertility.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] There is not enough water to continue farming using current practices; therefore how water, land, and ecosystem resources are used to boost crop yields must be reconsidered.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] A solution would be to give value to ecosystems, recognizing environmental and livelihood tradeoffs, and balancing the rights of a variety of users and interests.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Inequities that result when such measures are adopted would need to be addressed, such as the reallocation of water from poor to rich, the clearing of land to make way for more productive farmland, or the preservation of a wetland system that limits fishing rights.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Technological advancements help provide farmers with tools and resources to make farming more sustainable.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Technology permits innovations like conservation tillage, a farming process which helps prevent land loss to erosion, reduces water pollution, and enhances carbon sequestration.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Agricultural automation can help address some of the challenges associated with climate change and thus facilitate adaptation efforts.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] For example, the application of digital automation technologies (e.g. in precision agriculture) can improve resource-use efficiency in conditions which are increasingly constrained for agricultural producers.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Moreover, when applied to sensing and early warning, they can help address the uncertainty and unpredictability of weather conditions associated with accelerating climate change.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Other potential sustainable practices include conservation agriculture, agroforestry, improved grazing, avoided grassland conversion, and biochar.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Current mono-crop farming practices in the United States preclude widespread adoption of sustainable practices, such as 2–3 crop rotations that incorporate grass or hay with annual crops, unless negative emission goals such as soil carbon sequestration become policy.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] The food demand of Earth's projected population, with current climate change predictions, could be satisfied by improvement of agricultural methods, expansion of agricultural areas, and a sustainability-oriented consumer mindset.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Since the 1940s, agricultural productivity has increased dramatically, due largely to the increased use of energy-intensive mechanization, fertilizers and pesticides.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] The vast majority of this energy input comes from fossil fuel sources.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Between the 1960s and the 1980s, the Green Revolution transformed agriculture around the globe, with world grain production increasing significantly (between 70% and 390% for wheat and 60% to 150% for rice, depending on geographic area) as world population doubled.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Heavy reliance on petrochemicals has raised concerns that oil shortages could increase costs and reduce agricultural output.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Industrialized agriculture depends on fossil fuels in two fundamental ways: direct consumption on the farm and manufacture of inputs used on the farm.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Direct consumption includes the use of lubricants and fuels to operate farm vehicles and machinery.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Indirect consumption includes the manufacture of fertilizers, pesticides, and farm machinery.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] In particular, the production of nitrogen fertilizer can account for over half of agricultural energy usage.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Together, direct and indirect consumption by US farms accounts for about 2% of the nation's energy use.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Direct and indirect energy consumption by US farms peaked in 1979, and has since gradually declined.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Food systems encompass not just agriculture but off-farm processing, packaging, transporting, marketing, consumption, and disposal of food and food-related items.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Agriculture accounts for less than one-fifth of food system energy use in the US.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Plastic products are used extensively in agriculture, including to increase crop yields and improve the efficiency of water and agrichemical use.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] "Agriplastic" products include films to cover greenhouses and tunnels, mulch to cover soil (e.g. to suppress weeds, conserve water, increase soil temperature and aid fertilizer application), shade cloth, pesticide containers, seedling trays, protective mesh and irrigation tubing.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] The polymers most commonly used in these products are low-density polyethylene (LPDE), linear low-density polyethylene (LLDPE), polypropylene (PP) and polyvinyl chloride (PVC).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] The total amount of plastics used in agriculture is difficult to quantify.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] A 2012 study reported that almost 6.5 million tonnes per year were consumed globally while a later study estimated that global demand in 2015 was between 7.3 million and 9 million tonnes.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Widespread use of plastic mulch and lack of systematic collection and management have led to the generation of large amounts of mulch residue.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Weathering and degradation eventually cause the mulch to fragment.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] These fragments and larger pieces of plastic accumulate in soil.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Mulch residue has been measured at levels of 50 to 260 kg per hectare in topsoil in areas where mulch use dates back more than 10 years, which confirms that mulching is a major source of both microplastic and macroplastic soil contamination.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Agricultural plastics, especially plastic films, are not easy to recycle because of high contamination levels (up to 40–50% by weight contamination by pesticides, fertilizers, soil and debris, moist vegetation, silage juice water, and UV stabilizers) and collection difficulties .
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Therefore, they are often buried or abandoned in fields and watercourses or burned.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] These disposal practices lead to soil degradation and can result in contamination of soils and leakage of microplastics into the marine environment as a result of precipitation run-off and tidal washing.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] In addition, additives in residual plastic film (such as UV and thermal stabilizers) may have deleterious effects on crop growth, soil structure, nutrient transport and salt levels.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] There is a risk that plastic mulch will deteriorate soil quality, deplete soil organic matter stocks, increase soil water repellence and emit greenhouse gases.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Microplastics released through fragmentation of agricultural plastics can absorb and concentrate contaminants capable of being passed up the trophic chain.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Agricultural economics is economics as it relates to the "production, distribution and consumption of [agricultural] goods and services".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Combining agricultural production with general theories of marketing and business as a discipline of study began in the late 1800s, and grew significantly through the 20th century.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] In the United States, and elsewhere, food costs attributed to food processing, distribution, and agricultural marketing, sometimes referred to as the value chain, have risen while the costs attributed to farming have declined.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] This is related to the greater efficiency of farming, combined with the increased level of value addition (e.g. more highly processed products) provided by the supply chain.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Market concentration has increased in the sector as well, and although the total effect of the increased market concentration is likely increased efficiency, the changes redistribute economic surplus from producers (farmers) and consumers, and may have negative implications for rural communities.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] National government policies, such as taxation, subsidies, tariffs and others, can significantly change the economic marketplace for agricultural products.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Since at least the 1960s, a combination of trade restrictions, exchange rate policies and subsidies have affected farmers in both the developing and the developed world.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] In the 1980s, non-subsidized farmers in developing countries experienced adverse effects from national policies that created artificially low global prices for farm products.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Between the mid-1980s and the early 2000s, several international agreements limited agricultural tariffs, subsidies and other trade restrictions.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] However, as of 2009, there was still a significant amount of policy-driven distortion in global agricultural product prices.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] The three agricultural products with the most trade distortion were sugar, milk and rice, mainly due to taxation.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Among the oilseeds, sesame had the most taxation, but overall, feed grains and oilseeds had much lower levels of taxation than livestock products.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Since the 1980s, policy-driven distortions have decreases more among livestock products than crops during the worldwide reforms in agricultural policy.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Despite this progress, certain crops, such as cotton, still see subsidies in developed countries artificially deflating global prices, causing hardship in developing countries with non-subsidized farmers.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Unprocessed commodities such as corn, soybeans, and cattle are generally graded to indicate quality, affecting the price the producer receives.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Commodities are generally reported by production quantities, such as volume, number or weight.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Agricultural science is a broad multidisciplinary field of biology that encompasses the parts of exact, natural, economic and social sciences used in the practice and understanding of agriculture.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] The scientific study of agriculture began in the 18th century, when Johann Friedrich Mayer conducted experiments on the use of gypsum (hydrated calcium sulphate) as a fertilizer.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Research became more systematic when in 1843, John Lawes and Henry Gilbert began a set of long-term agronomy field experiments at Rothamsted Research Station in England; some of them, such as the Park Grass Experiment, are still running.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] In America, the Hatch Act of 1887 provided funding for what it was the first to call "agricultural science", driven by farmers' interest in fertilizers.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Agricultural policy is the set of government decisions and actions relating to domestic agriculture and imports of foreign agricultural products.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Governments usually implement agricultural policies with the goal of achieving a specific outcome in the domestic agricultural product markets.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Agricultural policy can also touch on food quality, ensuring that the food supply is of a consistent and known quality, food security, ensuring that the food supply meets the population's needs, and conservation.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Policy programs can range from financial programs, such as subsidies, to encouraging producers to enroll in voluntary quality assurance programs.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] A 2021 report finds that globally, support to agricultural producers accounts for almost US$540 billion a year.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] This amounts to 15 percent of total agricultural production value, and is heavily biased towards measures that are leading to inefficiency, as well as are unequally distributed and harmful for the environment and human health.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Crop use in animal agriculture accounts for one form of inefficiency.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Animal agriculture's estimated land use to produce one kilocalorie or gram of protein is 50 to 100 times that of plant-based alternatives.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Furthermore, the larger the livestock, the lower the energy efficiency (kilocalories obtained relative to kilocalories the animal consumes).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] For instance, beef's energy efficiency is estimated to be 2%.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] There are many influences on the creation of agricultural policy, including consumers, agribusiness, trade lobbies and other groups.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Agribusiness interests hold a large amount of influence over policy making, in the form of lobbying and campaign contributions.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Political action groups, including those interested in environmental issues and labor unions, also provide influence, as do lobbying organizations representing individual agricultural commodities.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] The Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) leads international efforts to defeat hunger and provides a forum for the negotiation of global agricultural regulations and agreements.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/agriculture-p02] Samuel Jutzi, director of FAO's animal production and health division, states that lobbying by large corporations has stopped reforms that would improve human health and the environment.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] Alex Segger George was born in Western Australia on 4 April 1939.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] George joined the Western Australian Herbarium as a laboratory assistant at the age of 20 in 1959.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] He worked under Charles Gardner for a year before the latter's retirement, and partly credits him with rekindling an interest in banksias.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] In 1963 he graduated with a Bachelor of Arts from the University of Western Australia, and the following year added a botany major.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] Continuing at the Western Australian Herbarium as a botanist, in 1968 he was seconded as Australian Botanical Liaison Officer at the Royal Botanic Gardens in London.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] George also has an interest in history, especially historical biography of naturalists in Western Australia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] He has published a number of articles in the field of history, including a history of the Royal Society of Western Australia and a tribute to naturalist and historian Rica Erickson.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] In 1999 he published a book on William Dampier's naturalist collections in Western Australia entitled *William Dampier in New Holland: Australia's First Natural Historian*.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] George initially specialised in orchids, but his focus gradually moved to the Proteaceae genera *Banksia* and *Dryandra* and later *Synaphea*.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] He contributed the text to Celia Rosser's three volume *The Banksias*, published between 1981 and 2001, which contains Rosser's paintings of every *Banksia* species.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] In 1981 *Nuytsia* published his landmark monograph "The genus *Banksia* L.f.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] (Proteaceae)", the first systematic treatment of the taxonomy of *Banksia* since George Bentham's *Flora Australiensis* appeared in the 1870s.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] Three years later he published the popular *The Banksia Book*, and the following year he published *An Introduction to the Proteaceae of Western Australia*.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] In 1999, his taxonomy of the *Banksia* and *Dryandra* genera was published as part of the *Flora of Australia* series of monographs.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] From 1981 to 1993, George lived in Canberra and worked as Executive Editor for the *Flora of Australia* series.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] His extensive revision of the genus *Verticordia*, an arrangement which included new taxa, was published in *Nuytsia* in 1991.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] He is now living in Perth again, and works as a botanical and editorial consultant.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] He is also an Honorary Research Associate with the Western Australian Herbarium, and an Adjunct Associate Professor with the College of Science, Murdoch University.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] Burbidge Medal from the Australasian Systematic Botany Society, and an honorary Doctor of Science from Murdoch University in 2009.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/alex-george-botanist] The genera *Alexgeorgea* and *Georgeantha*, and species *Buellia georgei* are named in his honour.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arid] The distribution of aridity at any time is largely the result of the general circulation of the atmosphere.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arid] The latter does change significantly over time through climate change.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arid] For example, temperature increase by 1.5–2.1 percent across the Nile Basin over the next 30–40 years could change the region from semi-arid to arid, significantly reducing the land usable for agriculture.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arid] In addition, changes in land use can increase demands on soil water and thereby increase aridity.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Arson is considered distinct from pyromania, an impulse control disorder characterized by an obsession with fire.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Most acts of arson are not committed by pyromaniacs.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Reckless burning is legally distinct from arson in some jurisdictions, but generally refers to cases where an individual causes a fire which results in death, destruction of property, or injury, through negligence or inattention.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Arsonists may set fires during riots, civil unrest, ethnic cleansing or war.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] An arsonist may commit the crime as an act of war, terrorism, for financial gain (i.e., insurance fraud or arson-for-profit), emotional satisfaction (i.e., firefighter arson, personal entertainment, retribution, or revenge), or in the concealment of another crime like robbery or homicide.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Fires are generally set using an accelerant (such as gasoline or kerosene) to ignite, propel, and direct the flames.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] The detection and identification of ignitable liquid residues is an important part of fire investigations.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] "burning"; and Edward Coke has indictment of *burning* (1640).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Arson has been a documented practice for centuries.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Arson (sometime called "fire setting" in scholarly literature) may have varying motivations, and can be difficult to profile.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Arson may be committed for a number of reasons.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] The wide variety of these motivations, along with limitations on cohort size, and variations in the scholarly, legal, social, and psychological definitions of arson/fire setting makes generalizations difficult.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] One or more individuals may commit arson during a riot as an act of vandalism, or during civil disorder or an ethnic cleansing as an act of war, terrorism or act of political protest.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] For instance, it is not uncommon for buildings, cars, dumpsters to be set on fire following sporting events in some cities and nations.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Fires may be set to provide "cover" to retreating or advancing forces, like in 1991 when the Iraqi military retreated from Kuwait.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Groups including the Provisional IRA and the Women's Social and Political Union have used arson as a political act of violence.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] During the most recent Myanmar civil war the Military junta engaged in a campaign of burning homes to drive out combatants in urban areas.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Inversely, arson (or intent to commit arson) has been used a false flag or smear campaign against activists, as in the case of Marinus van der Lubbe and Martin Sostre.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Other motivations include financial gain (i.e., a person destroys their own property by burning it and attempts to collect against their insurance policy).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In 2019 the California Department of Insurance and San Jose Fire Department were tipped off as to an insurance fraud scheme when the location of a planned incident was given to a tip line.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] After an investigation, a married couple and four co-conspirators were arrested and convicted with arson and insurance fraud after a string of home, business, and warehouse fires which took place over four years.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] The criminals left chicken in turned-on deep fryers to make the damage look like the result of a cooking accident.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] The group then filled insurance claims for the cost of the building, as well as smoke-damaged goods to claim fire damages for insurance payouts.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] The group's scheme claimed a reported $4 million before they were caught.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Fire may be set for emotional satisfaction, firefighter arson, personal entertainment, or as a tool of assault or revenge.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Arson investigator John Leonard Orr and other firefighter arsonists have been convicted of setting fires either personal entertainment or as a form of hero syndrome.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Arsonists may set a fire in an attempt to damage a small amount of property (as revenge against a landlord, employer, friend or relative) without understanding how quickly a fire can spread.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] The Dupont Plaza Hotel which killed 99 persons happened after three striking workers set fire to a storeroom of new furniture.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] The fire flashed over and ignited the ballroom and shortly, the rest of the hotel.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Artist Lisa Lopes accidentally burned down the mansion she shared with Andre Rison in 1994 after setting fire to his sneakers in a bathtub.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Many deadly fires have been set during or following arguments.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] A person may also commit arson as the result of a psychotic episode as a result of delusions or hallucinations and may or may not be found criminally insane.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Some arsonists have been committed to psychiatric hospitals instead of prison.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Additional reasons for arson include an attempt to conceal another crime like robbery or homicide.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] These attempts are often unsuccessful at hiding blunt trauma, stab wounds, and gunshot wounds.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Medical examiners may use a blood test and/or look for soot in the esophagus, lungs or mouth to check if the decedent was alive at the time of a fire.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Arson exists in a variety of legal definitions worldwide.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In many counties, including the Commonwealth, France, "arson" generally refers to a subsection of criminal or property damage.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Generally, offenses are more severe when human lives were endangered.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Some countries like Scotland differentiate the act of arson into wilful fire raising (the damage to property) and culpable and reckless conduct (injury to a person).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] English common law defines arson as "the malicious burning of the dwelling of another".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] For purposes of common law arson, "malicious" refers to intention of starting the fire.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Fires can be started on purpose or by accident.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] to charge the guilty person with arson whether their intention was to start a fire or not.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] "Malicious" in this case describes the intention of the arsonist as ill-intentioned and intending to cause harm or death.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] According to common law, charring to any part of a dwelling is sufficient to satisfy this element.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] No significant amount of damage to the dwelling is required.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Any injury or damage to the structure caused by exposure to heat or flame is sufficient.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] 'Dwelling' refers to a place of residence.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] At common law, a structure does not become a residence until the first occupants has moved in, and ceases to be a dwelling if the occupants abandon the premises with no intention of resuming their residency.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] 'Dwelling' includes structures and outbuildings within the curtilage.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] A barn can be the subject of arson if occupied as a dwelling.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Burning one's own dwelling does not constitute common law arson, even if the purpose were to collect insurance, because "it was generally assumed in early England that one had the legal right to destroy his own property in any manner he chose".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Moreover, for purposes of common law arson, possession or occupancy rather than title determines whose dwelling the structure is.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] while the landlord who set fire to a rented dwelling house he owned would be guilty.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In the United States, the common law elements of arson are often varied in different jurisdictions.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] For example, the element of "dwelling" is no longer required in most states, and arson occurs by the burning of any real property without consent or with unlawful intent.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Arson is prosecuted with attention to degree of severity in the alleged offense, but some states do not categorize arson by any degree.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In the state of Tennessee, arson is categorized as "arson" and "aggravated arson".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] First degree arson generally occurs when people are harmed or killed in the course of the fire, while second degree arson occurs when significant destruction of property occurs.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] While usually a felony, arson may also be prosecuted as a misdemeanor, "criminal mischief", or "destruction of property".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Burglary also occurs, if the arson involved a "breaking and entering".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In states with the death penalty and in federal law, a person may be sentenced to death if arson occurred as a method of homicide, as was the case in California of Raymond Lee Oyler and in Texas of Cameron Todd Willingham.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In several U.S. state legal systems (and nations like France) arson is divided into degrees depending the value of the property.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] It may also include additional penalties if the crime was committed during the day or night.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Many statutes vary the degree of the crime according to the criminal intent of the accused.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Some US states use other degrees of arson, such as "fourth" and "fifth" degree.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In New York, arson is charged in five degrees.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Arson in the first degree is a Class A-1 felony and requires the intent to burn the building with a person inside using an explosive incendiary device.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In New York, the criminal charge of arson includes a maximum sentence of 25 years to life.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In California, a conviction for arson of property that is not one's own is a felony punishable by up to three years in state prison.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Aggravated arson, which carries the most severe punishment for arson, is punishable by 10 years to life in state prison.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] A well-known example of arson which took place in California is the Esperanza Fire.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Raymond Lee Oyler was ultimately convicted of murder and sentenced to death for a 2006 fire in southern California that led to the deaths of five U.S.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Forest Service firefighters; he was the first U.S. citizen to receive such a conviction and penalty for wildfire arson.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Some states, such as California, prosecute the lesser offense of reckless burning when the fire is set recklessly as opposed to willfully and maliciously.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] The study of the causes is the subject of fire investigation.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] A recent example of a reckless burning offense is the El Dorado fire which took place in 2020 in California.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] This fire was caused by a gender reveal party which utilized a smoke bomb which is categorized as unsafe pyrotechnics.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] The El Dorado fire burned over a 71-day period, destroyed 20 structures and resulted in one firefighter fatality, for which the couple hosting the party were charged with involuntary manslaughter.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] The El Dorado Fire ultimately resulted in the death of firefighter Charles "Charlie" Morton, who became trapped while attempting to fight the fire.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] The DA of California considered arson charges for the family members as they were deemed negligent with regard to fire safety.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] During World War II, arson was a much higher concern in the United States.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] There was a severe lack of firefighters due to World War Two.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] There were few men left behind to help combat forest fires.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] For example, in Eldora, Iowa, a fire chief reported that his regular membership shrank from 21 to 9 men and their fire fighting force recruited retired members and new members to fill the missing positions during the war.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] There were additional concerns about wildfires on the west coast, especially following the 1942 Fu-Go balloon bomb incidents.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Rather than report on the incendiary bombs, the Office of Censorship instead focuses efforts on "reducing forest fires".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] On April 7, 2026, in Ontario, California, a warehouse employee was arrested on suspicion of arson after a large fire broke out in a Kimberly-Clark paper-goods warehouse.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] The suspect reportedly filmed the incident and uploaded the footage to social media while saying "If you're not going to pay us enough to fucking live or afford to live, at least pay us enough not to do this".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Three days later, on April 10, a second suspect was arrested on charges of arson after setting several small fires at the Ontario Mills mall.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] It is unknown if the two incidents were related.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In English law, arson was a common law offence until 1971 (except for the offence of arson in royal dockyards, which is statutory).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] The common law offence was abolished by section 11 (1) of the Criminal Damage Act 1971.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Section 1 (3) defines arson as criminal damage committed by fire; in contrast to common law arson, the property damaged or destroyed need not be a dwelling.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Section 4 of the Act provides a maximum penalty of life imprisonment for conviction on indictment.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] A variety of notable arsons have occurred in England.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In 1680 Margaret Clark and her accomplice John Satterthwayt burned down her employer's home.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Clark blamed her actions on pride and breaking the sabbath.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In 1791 in Birmingham, the Priestley Riots destroyed several buildings.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Between 1912 and 1914 women's suffragists like Emmeline Pankhurst, Emily Davison, and other women in Great Britain and Ireland launched a campaign of arson and bombings to obtain the vote for women.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Peter Dinsdale, AKA Bruce George Peter Lee, confessed to a total of 11 acts of arson, pleading guilty to 26 counts of manslaughter.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Michelle Confait was murdered in London in 1972 and her house was set alight.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In 2008, two students were found murdered in a flat in New Cross.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] The killer set the flat on fire to hide evidence.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In 1981 thirteen teenagers died as the result of a fire started at a house party in New Cross, the cause of which has been speculated to be arson (both investigations returned an open verdict).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In Hong Kong, the common law offence was abolished by s.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] 67 of the Crimes Ordinance 1971 (Part VIII of which, as amended by the Crimes (Amendment) Ordinance 1972, mirrored the English Criminal Damage Act 1971).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Like the English counterparts, section 63 of the 1972 Ordinance provides a maximum penalty of life imprisonment, and s.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] 60(3) of the Ordinance requires that if the damage is by fire the offence should be charged as arson.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] A Molotov cocktail damaged a metro station during the 2019–2020 Hong Kong protests.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Fire bombs, molotov cocktails and other incendiary devices were commonly used by militants during The Troubles.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In 2025 several buildings were destroyed along with motorbikes and vehicles in a riot following a sexual assault.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In the Burmese legal system, arson is considered "mischief by fire" under sections 435 and 436 of the Myanmar Penal Code and punishable by fine and imprisonment.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] The statutes were last amended on 1 July 2016, and made arson on houses and buildings punishable with up to 20 years in prison.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] A number of buildings were set on fire during the U Thant funeral crisis in 1974.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In 2013 a series of riots resulted in a number of arson related deaths after anti-Muslim riots.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] The Burmese military has long used arson as a weapon of war against civilians.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Between the 2021 Myanmar coup d'état and August 2022, military forces committed arson on 28,434 houses in the country.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] While the Scottish legal system has no offence known as arson statutorily defined, there are many offences that are used to charge those with acts that would normally constitute arson in other nations.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Events constituting arson in English and Welsh law might be dealt with as one or more of a variety of offences such as wilful fire-raising, culpable and reckless conduct, vandalism or other offences depending on the circumstances of the event.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] The more serious offences (in particular wilful fire-raising and culpable and reckless conduct) can incur a sentence of life imprisonment.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In 2023, three young boys were charged in connection with the Ayr Station Hotel fire.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In Kilmarnock, two boys were arrested after accidentally burning down several buildings.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Ireland differentiates how it charges arson not by degree but rather by what is being destroyed and if anyone was harmed.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] For example, while the sentence for setting fire to a building can be life imprisonment, the sentence for setting fire to goods in a building can only be up to fourteen years.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] A notable historical act of arson in Ireland is the burning of Wildgoose Lodge, which resulted in the arrest, sentencing, and execution of 18 men, many of whom were innocent.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] More recently, the 2023 Dublin riot involved instances of arson, with many such acts targeting vehicles.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Murrough O'Brien, 1st Earl of Inchiquin, an Irish nobleman and soldier, was known as *Murchadh na dTóiteán* ("Murrough the Burner") for his role in the Sack of Cashel and other similar atrocities during the Cromwellian conquest of Ireland.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] In the Philippines, arson, alongside almost all illegal acts is governed by the Revised Penal Code (RPC).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] 1613, arson is generally divided into two categories: Simple Arson and Destructive Arson.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Simple Arson constitutes intentional burning of property that excludes any serious and aggravating circumstances that would elevate the crime to destructive arson.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Examples are the burning of houses, cars, vehicles, crops, etc.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] On the other hand, Destructive Arson is a more severe form of arson, characterized by extensive damages to the property and poses a direct threat to public safety.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/arson] Examples include structures that maybe inhabited or occupied, buildings intended for public use, the intentional burning of a property that poses a direct threat to life and the burning of industrial establishments or facilities.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians began arriving from Southeast Asia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, during the Last Glacial Period.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] By the time of British settlement, Aboriginal Australians spoke more than 250 distinct languages and had one of the oldest living cultures in the world.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia's written history commenced with Dutch exploration of most of the coastline in the 17th century.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] British colonisation began in 1788 with the establishment of the penal colony of New South Wales.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] By the mid-19th century, most of the continent had been explored by European settlers and five additional self-governing British colonies were established, each gaining responsible government by 1890.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The colonies federated in 1901, forming the Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] This continued a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom, highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster Adoption Act 1942*, and culminating in the *Australia Act 1986*.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia is a parliamentary democracy with a constitutional monarchy, and a federation comprising six states and ten territories.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Its population of almost 29 million is highly urbanised and heavily concentrated on the eastern seaboard.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Canberra is the nation's capital, while its most populous cities are Sydney and Melbourne, each with a population of more than five million.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia's culture is diverse, and the country has one of the highest foreign-born populations in the world.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] It has a highly developed economy and one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade relations are crucial to the country's economy.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] It ranks highly for quality of life, health, education, economic freedom, civil liberties and political rights.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, and has the world's thirteenth-highest military expenditure.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] It is a member of international groups including: the United Nations, the G20, the OECD, the World Trade Organization, Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community and the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia also participates in the defence, intelligence and security alliances ANZUS, AUKUS and Five Eyes.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] It is a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The name *Australia* (pronounced /əˈstreɪliə/ in Australian English) is derived from the Latin *Terra Australis Incognita* ('unknown southern land'), a name used for a hypothetical continent in the Southern Hemisphere since ancient times.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Several 16th-century cartographers used the word *Australia* on maps, but not to identify modern Australia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] When the Dutch began visiting and mapping Australia in the 17th century, they called the continent *New Holland*.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The name *Australia* was popularised by the explorer Matthew Flinders, who circumnavigated the continent in 1803.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] However, when his account of his voyage was published in 1814, the name *Terra Australis* was used.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Governor of New South Wales Lachlan Macquarie officially recommended the name *Australia* to replace *New Holland* in December 1817.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The British Admiralty adopted the name in 1824, and the British Parliament used it in legislation in 1828.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The United Kingdom Hydrographic Office used the new name in *The Australia Directory* of 1830.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The name "Commonwealth of Australia" for the new federation of the six former colonies was formalised in the *Commonwealth of Australia Constitution Act 1900* (UK).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Colloquial names for Australia include "Oz", "Straya" and "Down Under".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Human habitation of the Australian continent is estimated to have begun 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, with the migration of people by land bridges and short sea crossings from what is now Southeast Asia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] It is uncertain how many waves of immigration may have contributed to these ancestors of modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Madjedbebe rock shelter in Arnhem Land is possibly the oldest site showing the presence of humans in Australia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The oldest human remains found are the Lake Mungo remains, which have been dated to approximately 42,000 years ago.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australian culture is one of the oldest continuous cultures on Earth.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] At the time of first European contact, Aboriginal Australians belonged to wide range of societies, with diverse economies spread across at least 250 different language groups.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Estimates of the Aboriginal population before British settlement range from 300,000 to 3 million.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australians cultures were (and remain) deeply connected with the land and the environment, with stories of The Dreaming maintained through oral tradition, songs, dance and paintings.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Certain groups engaged in fire-stick farming, fish farming, and built semi-permanent shelters.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] These practices have variously been characterised as "hunter-gatherer", "agricultural", "natural cultivation" and "intensification".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Torres Strait Islander people first settled their islands at least 2,500 years ago.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Culturally and linguistically distinct from mainland Aboriginal peoples, they were seafarers and obtained their livelihood from seasonal horticulture and the resources of their reefs and seas.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Agriculture also developed on some islands and villages appeared by the 1300s.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] By the mid-18th century in northern Australia, contact, trade and cross-cultural engagement had been established between local Aboriginal groups and Makassan trepangers, visiting from present-day Indonesia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In 1606 the crew of the Dutch ship, *Duyfken*, captained by Willem Janszoon, made the first documented European landing in Australia and contact with Aboriginal Australians.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Later that year, Luís Vaz de Torres sailed to the north of Australia through Torres Strait, along New Guinea's southern coast.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Abel Tasman's voyage of 1642 was the first known European expedition to reach Van Diemen's Land.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] On his second voyage of 1644, he mapped the north coast of Australia south of New Guinea.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Following Tasman's voyages, the Dutch were able to make almost complete maps of Australia's northern and western coasts and much of its southern and south-eastern Tasmanian coasts.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In 1770, Captain James Cook sailed along and mapped the east coast, which he named "New South Wales" and claimed for Great Britain.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In 1786, the British government announced its intention to establish a penal colony in New South Wales.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] On 26 January 1788, the First Fleet commanded by Captain Arthur Phillip, arrived at Sydney Cove, Port Jackson.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] A camp was established and the Union Flag raised and the date later became Australia's national day.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Most early settlers were convicts, transported for petty crimes and assigned as labourers or servants to "free settlers" (willing immigrants).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Once emancipated, convicts tended to integrate into colonial society.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Aboriginal resistance, convict rebellions and bushranging were sometimes suppressed under martial law.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The 1808 Rum Rebellion, carried out by officers of the New South Wales Corp, led to a temporary military junta.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] During the next two decades, social and economic reforms, together with the establishment of a Legislative Council and Supreme Court, saw the penal colony transition to a civil society.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The indigenous population declined for 150 years following European settlement, mainly due to infectious disease.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] British colonial authorities did not sign any treaties with Aboriginal groups.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] As settlement expanded, tens of thousands of Indigenous people and thousands of settlers were killed in frontier conflicts, which many historians argue included acts of genocide by settlers.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Settlers dispossessed surviving Indigenous peoples of most of their land.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In 1803, a settlement was established in Van Diemen's Land (present-day Tasmania), and in 1813, Gregory Blaxland, William Lawson and William Wentworth crossed the Blue Mountains west of Sydney, opening the interior to European settlement.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The British claim was extended to the whole Australian continent in 1827 when Major Edmund Lockyer established a settlement on King George Sound (modern-day Albany).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Swan River Colony (present-day Perth) was established in 1829, evolving into the largest Australian colony by area, Western Australia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Separate colonies were carved from New South Wales: Tasmania in 1825, South Australia in 1836, Victoria in 1851, and Queensland in 1859.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] South Australia and Victoria were founded as free colonies – they never accepted transported convicts.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Growing opposition to the convict system culminated in its abolition in the eastern colonies by the 1850s.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Initially a free colony, Western Australia accepted convicts from 1850 to 1868.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The six colonies individually gained responsible government between 1855 and 1890, managing most of their own affairs while remaining part of the British Empire.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Colonial Office in London retained control of some matters, notably foreign affairs.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The colonial parliaments progressively extended voting rights to adult men from 1856, with women's suffrage on equal terms following between the 1890s and 1900s.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Some colonies introduced racial restrictions on voting from 1885.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In the mid-19th century, explorers such as Burke and Wills charted Australia's interior.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] A series of gold rushes beginning in the early 1850s led to an influx of new migrants from China, North America and continental Europe, as well as outbreaks of bushranging and civil unrest; the latter peaked in 1854 when Ballarat miners launched the Eureka Rebellion against gold licence fees.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The 1860s saw the rise of blackbirding, where South Sea Islanders were coerced or abducted into indentured labour, mainly by Queensland colonists.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] From 1886, Australian colonial governments began removing many Aboriginal children from their families and communities, justified on the grounds of child protection and forced assimilation policies.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Second Boer War (1899–1902) marked the largest overseas deployment of Australia's colonial forces.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] On 1 January 1901, federation of the colonies was achieved after a decade of planning, constitutional conventions and referendums, resulting in the establishment of the Commonwealth of Australia as a nation under the new Australian Constitution.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] From 1901, Australia was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] It was one of the founding members of the League of Nations in 1920, and the United Nations in 1945.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The *Statute of Westminster 1931* ended the ability of the UK to legislate for Australia at the federal level without Australia's consent.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia adopted it in 1942, but it was backdated to 1939 to confirm the validity of legislation passed during World War II.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Australian Capital Territory was formed in 1911 as the location for the future federal capital of Canberra.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] While it was being constructed, Melbourne served as the temporary capital from 1901 to 1927.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Northern Territory was transferred from South Australia to the Commonwealth in 1911.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia took over the administration of the Territory of Papua (previously British New Guinea) in 1905 and of the Territory of New Guinea (formerly German New Guinea) in 1920.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The two were unified as the Territory of Papua and New Guinea in 1949 and gained independence from Australia in 1975.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In 1914, Australia joined the Allies in the First World War, and took part in the fighting on several fronts.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Of the 324,000 men who served overseas, about 60,000 were killed and another 152,000 were wounded.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Many Australians regard the defeat of the Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (ANZAC) at Gallipoli in 1915 as the "baptism of fire" that forged the new nation's identity.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The beginning of the campaign is commemorated annually on Anzac Day, a date which rivals Australia Day as the nation's most important.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] From 1939 to 1945, Australia joined the Allies in fighting the Second World War.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia's armed forces fought in the Pacific, European and Mediterranean and Middle East theatres.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Since 1951, Australia has maintained a mutual security alliance with the United States under the ANZUS treaty.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In the three decades following World War II, Australia experienced significant increases in living standards, leisure time and suburban development.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Governments encouraged a large wave of immigration from across Europe and called these migrants "New Australians".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] High immigration was justified to Australians using the slogan "populate or perish", and from the 1960s the white Australia policy was gradually relaxed.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] A member of the Western Bloc during the Cold War, Australia participated in the Korean War and the Malayan Emergency during the 1950s and the Vietnam War from 1962 to 1973.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Tensions over communist influence in society led to unsuccessful attempts by the Menzies Government to ban the Communist Party of Australia, and a bitter split in the Labor Party in 1955.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] As a result of a 1967 referendum, the federal government gained the power to legislate with regard to Aboriginal Australians, and Aboriginal Australians were fully included in the census.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Pre-colonial land interests (referred to as native title in Australia) was recognised in law for the first time when the High Court of Australia held in *Mabo v Queensland (No 2)* that Australia was not *terra nullius* ('land belonging to no one') at the time of European settlement.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Following the abolition of the last vestiges of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia's demography and culture transformed as a result of a large and ongoing wave of non-European immigration, mostly from Asia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The late 20th century also saw an increasing focus on foreign policy ties with other Asia–Pacific nations.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Australia Acts of 1986 severed the remaining constitutional ties between Australia and the United Kingdom while maintaining the monarch in her independent capacity as Queen of Australia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In a 1999 constitutional referendum, 55% of voters rejected abolishing the monarchy and becoming a republic.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Following the September 11 attacks in the United States, Australia joined the United States in fighting the Afghanistan War from 2001 to 2021 and the Iraq War from 2003 to 2009.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The nation's trade relations also became increasingly oriented towards East Asia in the 21st century, with China becoming the nation's largest trading partner by a large margin.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, from March 2020 lockdowns and other restrictions on public gatherings and movement across the national and state borders were implemented by the Federal, state and territory governments.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Following the rollout of vaccines in 2021, these restrictions were gradually eased.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In October 2023, Australia declared that COVID-19 was no longer a communicable disease incident of national significance.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia consists of the mainland Australian continent, the island of Tasmania, numerous smaller offshore islands, and the remote offshore territories of Ashmore and Cartier Islands, Christmas Island, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Coral Sea Islands, Heard and McDonald Islands, and Norfolk Island.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia also claims about 42% of Antarctica as the Australian Antarctic Territory, but this claim is only recognised by four other countries.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Mainland Australia lies between latitudes 9° and 44° south, and longitudes 112° and 154° east.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Surrounded by the Indian and Pacific oceans, Australia is separated from Asia by the Arafura and Timor seas, with the Coral Sea lying off the Queensland coast, and the Tasman Sea lying between Australia and New Zealand.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Great Barrier Reef, the world's largest coral reef, lies a short distance off the north-east coast and extends for more than 2,300 km (1,400 mi).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The mainland is the world's smallest continent and the country is the sixth-largest by total area.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia is sometimes considered the world's largest island and is often dubbed the "island continent".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] It has 35,877 km (22,293 mi) of coastline (excluding all offshore islands), and claims an exclusive economic zone of 8,148,250 square kilometres (3,146,060 sq mi).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] This exclusive economic zone does not include the Australian Antarctic Territory.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In 2021, Australia had 10% of the global permanent meadows and pastureland.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Forest cover is about 17% of Australia's land area.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Australian mainland is relatively flat, with an average height of 325 metres (1,066 ft) compared with 870 metres (2,850 ft) for all continents.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Great Dividing Range runs along most of eastern Australia, dividing the central lowlands from the eastern highlands.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] At 2,228 m (7,310 ft), Mount Kosciuszko is the highest mountain on the mainland.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Taller are Mawson Peak, at 2,745 m (9,006 ft), on Heard Island, and, in the Australian Antarctic Territory, Mount McClintock and Mount Menzies, at 3,492 m (11,457 ft) and 3,355 m (11,007 ft) respectively.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Murray-Darling is the major river system, draining most of inland New South Wales and Southern Queensland towards Lake Alexandrina and the sea in South Australia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] There are also smaller coastal river systems, inland drainage systems such as the Lake Eyre system, and salt lake systems in central and western Australia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia's rivers have the lowest discharge into the sea of any continent.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The mainland's flat, arid profile also makes its rivers slow-moving, resulting in a build up of salt on the land.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Salinisation adversely affects Australia's soil which is, on average, poor in nutrients compared with world standards.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia's population is concentrated on the coastal fringes.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] About 95% of the population lives within 100 km of the coast; the world average is 39%.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia's population density is 3.5 inhabitants per square kilometre, which is one of the lowest in the world.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] However, there is a large concentration of the population in cities along the temperate south-eastern coastline, and population density exceeds 38 inhabitants per square kilometre in central Melbourne.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Formerly part of the Rodinia and Gondwana supercontinents, Australia completely separated from Antarctica about 35 million years ago and continued drifting northwards.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] When the Last Glacial Period ended, rising sea levels separated the Australian mainland from New Guinea about 8,000 years ago and from Tasmania about 6,000 years ago.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia lies well within the Australian tectonic plate.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The mainland is relatively stable geologically, with no major mountain building, active volcanoes or tectonic faults.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] However, the Australian plate is moving north-northeast at a rate of about 6 to 7 cm a year and is currently in collision with the Eurasian plate and Pacific plate.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The resulting intratectonic stresses lead to relatively high seismic activity for a geologically stable landmass.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] There were 18 earthquakes with a moment magnitude of greater than 6 between 1901 and 2017.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Newcastle earthquake of 1989 was Australia's deadliest, killing 13 people.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] There were active volcanoes on the eastern mainland as recently as 4,600 years ago, and this is reflected in Aboriginal place names and creation stories.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Currently, volcanism occurs in the remote Heard Island and McDonald Islands.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Australian continental crust was created in three cycles from the oldest Archaean cratons in the west to the younger orogenic formations in the east (built about 541 million to 252 million years ago).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The oldest Australian surface rocks date to the Archaean period.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Some in Western Australia are older than 3.7 billion years and others in South Australia are over 3.1 billion years old.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The oldest zircon crystals on Earth, dating back 4.4 billion years, have been found in Western Australia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] However, about 80 per cent of Australia is covered by sedimentary rocks and regolith that are less than 250 million years old.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Australian climate ranges from wet tropical in the northeast and northwest to arid in the centre.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The coastal south is temperate and humid with winter freezing and snow in the southeastern highlands and Tasmania.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The climate is influenced by Australia's position in the "horse latitudes", which tends to bring arid conditions.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Overall, the Australian mainland is the driest inhabited continent, with an average annual rainfall of 470 millimetres (19 in).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] About 70% of the country is arid or semi-arid, and about 18% is desert.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The climate is also influenced by various systems such as the El Niño–Southern Oscillation, the Indian Ocean Dipole and the Southern Annular Mode.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia has unusual variability in rainfall within years and between years, leading to frequent droughts and flooding.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Cyclones and rain depressions are common in tropical Australia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The summer monsoon brings significant rainfall to northern Australia and low pressure cells bring winter rainfall in the south.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The hottest regions are in the northwest of the country and the coolest in the southeast.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Bushfire conditions are common in southern Australia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Climate change from increased greenhouse gas emissions has led to a 1.5 °C rise in Australian temperatures since 1910 and an increase in extreme heat and heavy rainfall events.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] There has been a reduction in rainfall from April to October in southern Australia since 1970 and a longer bushfire season since the 1950s.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Rainfall has increased in northern Australia since the 1970s.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The number of tropical cyclones has fallen since 1982 and alpine snow has decreased since the late 1950s.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Sea levels are rising around Australia and the surrounding oceans are becoming more acidic.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia is one of 17 megadiverse countries.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Because of its long geographic isolation, much of Australia's biota is unique.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] About 94% of its amphibians, 93% of its reptiles and flowering plants, 69% of its mammals and 46% of its birds are endemic.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia has a wide range of ecosystems of which 89 regions and 419 subregions are recognised in the Australian bioregion framework.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In January 2025, there were 168,386 named species on the Australian National Species List.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] However, it is estimated that 70% of Australian species have not been discovered and classified and that there may be 600,000 Australian native species.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In general, knowledge of vertebrates and flowering plants is better than for invertebrates and fungi.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] It is estimated that less that 10% of Australia's fungi and insects have been named.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] About 10% of the world's known plant species are found in Australia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Many of these have adapted to the arid climate, variable rainfall and nutrient-poor soil.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Deserts and xeric shrubland cover about 70% of the mainland.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Acacia, banksia and eucalypts have spread over much of Australia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Many plants have hard and long-living leaves, and are rich in carbon, poor in nutrients, and well adapted to bushfires.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] About two-thirds of the world's 330 species of marsupials are native to Australia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australian placental mammals (overwhelmingly bats, rats and mice) also make up almost 47% of the world's land mammal species.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia has about 10% of the world's known reptile species.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] There are also about 320,500 invertebrate species, of which insects are the largest class, accounting for more than 75% of all animal species.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia has over 15,000 known species of fungi, although it is possible that tens of thousands more exist.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia's wildlife show many adaptations to their environments.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] As the leaves of most plants are poor in nutrients, Australia has a high proportion of birds, insects and marsupials, such as the honey possum, that feed on nectar and pollen.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The koala is an exception, specialising in feeding on eucalyptus leaves.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Nutritionally poor flora and variable rainfall also favour animals with lower energy requirements, including snakes, lizards, and hopping marsupials such as the kangaroo and wallaby.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] There is, however, evidence of convergent evolution of Australia's marsupials and the placental mammals of other continents living in similar environments.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] For example, the extinct thylacine (Tasmanian tiger) had similarities with the placental wolf, marsupial moles with the golden moles of Africa, and hopping mice with the hopping rodents of other arid regions.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] There were major extinctions of Australia's vertebrates, including its megafauna, about 46 thousand years ago, and there is an ongoing scientific debate over the role of human activity and climate change in these extinctions.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The contraction of the range of the Tasmanian tiger and Tasmanian devil to that island about 4,000 to 5,000 years ago is also consistent with changes on the mainland including an increasing human population, the introduction of the dingo, and the greater use of fire and new stone tool technologies.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Over the past two centuries, Australia has lost more mammal species than any other continent.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Overall, 100 Australian species are listed as extinct or extinct in the wild.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In June 2021, over 1,000 animal and plant species were listed by Australian governments as endangered or critically endangered.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The major threats to endangered species are landscape change, ecosystem disruption, introduced species such as the feral cat and red fox, and climate change.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The federal *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* is the legal framework for the protection of threatened species.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The National Reserve System is Australia's network of protected areas.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] As at 30 June 2022, it covered over 22% of Australia's land mass.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] *Australia's Strategy for Nature 2024–2030* is the national biodiversity plan that aims to reverse biodiversity loss in Australia by 2030 and meet the county's obligations under the United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity and other international agreements.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia is a constitutional monarchy, a parliamentary democracy and a federation.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The country has maintained its mostly unchanged constitution alongside a stable liberal democratic political system since Federation in 1901.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] It is one of the world's oldest federations, in which power is divided between the federal and state governments.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Following elections on 3 May 2025, the prime minister is Anthony Albanese of the Australian Labor Party.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Charles III reigns as King of Australia and is represented in Australia by the governor-general at the federal level and by the governors at the state level, who by section 63 of the Constitution and convention act on the advice of their ministers.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Thus, in practice the governor-general acts as a legal figurehead for the actions of the prime minister and the Cabinet.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The governor-general may in some situations exercise reserve powers: powers exercisable in the absence of, or contrary to, ministerial advice.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] When these powers may be exercised is governed by convention and their precise scope is unclear.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The most notable exercise of these powers was the dismissal of the Whitlam government in the constitutional crisis of 1975.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In the Senate (the upper house), there are 76 senators: twelve each from the states and two each from the mainland territories (the Australian Capital Territory and the Northern Territory).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The House of Representatives (the lower house) has 150 members elected from single-member electoral divisions, commonly known as "electorates" or "seats", allocated to states on the basis of population, with each of the current states guaranteed a minimum of five seats.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The lower house has a maximum term of three years, but this is not fixed and governments usually dissolve the house early for an election at some point in the 6 months before the maximum.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Elections for both chambers are generally held simultaneously with senators having overlapping six-year terms except for those from the territories, whose terms are not fixed but are tied to the electoral cycle for the lower house.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Thus, only 40 of the 76 places in the Senate are put to each election unless the cycle is interrupted by a double dissolution.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia's electoral system uses preferential voting for the House of Representatives and all state and territory lower house elections (with the exception of Tasmania and the ACT which use the Hare-Clark system).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Senate and most state upper houses use the proportional system which combines preferential voting with proportional representation for each state.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Voting and enrolment is compulsory for all enrolled citizens 18 years and older in every jurisdiction.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The party with majority support in the House of Representatives forms the government and its leader becomes prime minister.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The governor-general appoints the prime minister and may dismiss one who has lost the confidence of parliament or acts illegally.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] As Australia is a Westminster parliamentary democracy with a powerful and elected upper house, its system has sometimes been called a "Washminster mutation", or semi-parliamentary.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] There are two major political groups that have usually formed government federally: the Australian Labor Party and the Coalition which is a grouping of the Liberal Party and its minor partner, the National Party.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Within Australian political culture, the Labor Party is considered centre-left and the Coalition is considered centre-right.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Independent members and several minor parties have achieved representation in Australian parliaments, mostly in upper houses.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Australian Greens have been the third largest party by both vote and membership since 2004.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia has six states – New South Wales (NSW), Victoria (Vic), Queensland (Qld), Western Australia (WA), South Australia (SA) and Tasmania (Tas) – and two mainland self-governing territories – the Australian Capital Territory (ACT) and the Northern Territory (NT).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The states have the general power to make laws except in the few areas where the constitution grants the Commonwealth (the federal level of government) exclusive powers.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Commonwealth can only make laws on topics listed in the constitution but its laws prevail over those of the states to the extent of any inconsistency.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Since Federation, the Commonwealth's power relative to the states has significantly increased due to the increasingly wide interpretation given to listed Commonwealth powers – and because of the states' heavy financial reliance on Commonwealth grants.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Each state and major mainland territory has its own parliament – unicameral in the Northern Territory, the ACT and Queensland, and bicameral in the other states.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The lower houses are known as the Legislative Assembly (the House of Assembly in South Australia and Tasmania); the upper houses are known as the Legislative Council.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The head of the government in each state is the premier and in each territory the chief minister.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The King is represented in each state by a governor.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] At the Commonwealth level, the King's representative is the governor-general.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The remote Macquarie Island and Lord Howe Island are part of Tasmania and New South Wales respectively.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, whose foreign relations has three core bi-partisan pillars: commitment to the US alliance, engagement with the Indo-Pacific and support for international institutions, rules and co-operation.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Through the ANZUS pact and its status as a major non-NATO ally, Australia maintains a close relationship with the US, which encompasses strong defence, security and trade ties.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In the Indo-Pacific, the country seeks to increase its trade ties through the open flow of trade and capital, while managing the rise of Chinese power by supporting the existing rules-based order.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Regionally, the country is a member of the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community, the ASEAN+6 mechanism and the East Asia Summit.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Internationally, the country is a member of the United Nations (of which it was a founding member), the Commonwealth of Nations, the OECD and the G20.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] This reflects the country's generally strong commitment to multilateralism.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia has pursued the cause of international trade liberalisation.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] It led the formation of the Cairns Group and Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, and is a member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia maintains a deeply integrated relationship with neighbouring New Zealand, with free mobility of citizens between the two countries under the Trans-Tasman Travel Arrangement and free trade under the Closer Economic Relations agreement.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The most favourably viewed countries by the Australian people in 2021 include New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Japan, Germany, Taiwan, Thailand, the United States and South Korea.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] It also maintains an international aid program under which some 75 countries receive assistance.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia ranked fourth in the Center for Global Development's 2021 Commitment to Development Index.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The power over foreign policy is highly concentrated in the prime minister and the national security committee, with major decision such as joining the 2003 invasion of Iraq made without prior Cabinet approval.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Similarly, the Parliament does not play a formal role in foreign policy and the power to declare war lies solely with the executive government.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade supports the executive in its policy decisions.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The two main institutions involved in the management of Australia's armed forces are the Australian Defence Force (ADF) and the Department of Defence, together known as "Defence".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Australian Defence Force is the military wing, headed by the chief of the defence force, and contains three branches: the Royal Australian Navy, the Australian Army and the Royal Australian Air Force.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In 2021, it had 84,865 currently serving personnel (including 60,286 regulars and 24,581 reservists).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Department of Defence is the civilian wing and is headed by the secretary of defence.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] These two leaders collective manage Defence as a diarchy, with shared and joint responsibilities.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The titular role of commander-in-chief is held by the governor-general; however, actual command is vested in the chief of the Defence Force.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The executive branch of the Commonwealth government has overall control of the military through the minister of defence, who is subject to the decisions of Cabinet and its National Security Committee.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Major Australian intelligence agencies include the Australian Secret Intelligence Service (foreign intelligence), the Australian Signals Directorate (signals intelligence) and the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation (domestic security).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In 2022, defence spending was 1.9% of GDP, representing the world's 13th-largest defence budget.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia has generally strong protections for civil and political rights, and the country has signed up to a wide range of international rights treaties.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Important documents protecting human rights include the Constitution, the *Racial Discrimination Act 1975*, the *Sex Discrimination Act 1984*, the *Disability Discrimination Act 1992*, and the *Age Discrimination Act 2004*.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Same-sex marriage has been legal in the nation since 2017.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Unlike other comparable Western democracies, Australia does not have a single federal charter of rights in the Constitution or under legislation; however, the ACT, Victoria, and Queensland have state-based ones.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] International organisations such as Human Rights Watch and Amnesty International have expressed concerns in areas including asylum-seeker policy, Indigenous deaths in custody, the lack of entrenched rights protection, and laws restricting protesting.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia's mixed-market economy is highly developed and rich in natural resources.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] It is the world's twelfth largest by nominal terms, and the twenty-third largest by PPP.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] As of 2021, Australia has the second-highest amount of wealth per adult, after Luxembourg, and the thirteenth-highest financial assets per capita, as well as one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] It has a labour force of some 13.5 million, with an unemployment rate of 3.5% as of June 2022.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] According to the Australian Council of Social Service, the poverty rate of Australia exceeds 13.6% of the population, encompassing over 3.2 million.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] It also estimated that there were 774,000 (17.7%) children under the age of 15 living in relative poverty.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The Australian dollar is the national currency, which is also used by three island states in the Pacific: Kiribati, Nauru, and Tuvalu.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australian government debt, about $963 billion in June 2022, exceeds 45.1% of the country's total GDP, and is the world's eighth-highest.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia had the second-highest level of household debt in the world in 2020, after Switzerland.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Its house prices are among the highest in the world, especially in the large urban areas.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The large service sector accounts for about 71.2% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (25.3%), while its agriculture sector makes up 3.6% of total GDP.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia is the world's 21st-largest exporter and 24th-largest importer.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] China is Australia's largest trading partner, accounting for roughly 40% of the country's exports and 17.6% of its imports.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Other major export markets include Japan, the United States, and South Korea.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia has high levels of competitiveness and economic freedom, and was ranked tenth in the Human Development Index in 2022.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] As of 2022, it is ranked twelfth in the Index of Economic Freedom.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] It attracted 9.5 million international tourists in 2019, and was ranked thirteenth among the countries of Asia-Pacific in 2019 for inbound tourism.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The 2021 *Travel and Tourism Competitiveness Report* ranked Australia seventh-highest in the world out of 117 countries.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Its international tourism receipts in 2019 amounted to $45.7 billion.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Total consumption of energy in this period was sourced from coal (28.4%), oil (37.3%), gas (27.4%) and renewables (7%).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] From 2012 to 2022, the energy sourced from renewables has increased 5.7%, while energy sourced from coal has decreased 2.6%.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] The use of gas also increased by 1.5% and the use of oil stayed relatively stable with a reduction of only 0.2%.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In 2020, Australia produced 27.7% of its electricity from renewable sources, exceeding the target set by the Commonwealth government in 2009 of 20% renewable energy by 2020.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] A new target of 82% renewable energy by 2030 was set in 2022 and a target for net zero emissions by 2050 was set in 2021.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In 2019, Australia spent $35.6 billion on research and development, allocating about 1.79% of GDP.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] A 2022 study by the industry lobby group, The Tech Council of Australia, stated that the Australian technology sector combined contributes $167 billion a year to the economy and employs 861,000 people.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] In 2022, startup ecosystems in Sydney and Melbourne were valued at $34 billion.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australia ranked 22nd in the Global Innovation Index 2025.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] With only 0.3% of the world's population, Australia contributed over 4% of the world's published research in 2020, making it one of the top 10 research contributors in the world.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] CSIRO, Australia's national science agency, contributes 10% of all research in the country, while the rest is carried out by universities.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Australian achievements include the invention of atomic absorption spectroscopy, the essential components of Wi-Fi technology, and the development of the first commercially successful polymer banknote.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] As of 2026, 14 Australian scientists have been awarded the Nobel Prize in physics, chemistry or medicine, and two have been awarded the Fields Medal.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p01] Facilities supporting space exploration include the Square Kilometre Array and Australia Telescope Compact Array radio telescopes, telescopes such as the Siding Spring Observatory, and ground stations such as the Canberra Deep Space Communication Complex.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The population of Australia is estimated to be 27,724,744 as of September 2025.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] It is the 54th most populous country in the world and the most populous Oceanian country.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australia has a population density of 3.4 persons per square kilometre of total land area, which makes it one of the most sparsely populated countries in the world.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The population is heavily concentrated on the east coast, and in particular in the south-eastern region between South East Queensland to the north-east and Adelaide to the south-west.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australia is also highly urbanised, with 67% of the population living in the Greater Capital City Statistical Areas (metropolitan areas of the state and mainland territorial capital cities) in 2018.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Metropolitan areas with more than one million inhabitants are Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Perth and Adelaide.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Australia is experiencing a demographic shift towards an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] In 2021, the average age of the population was 39 years.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australia has five cities (including their suburbs) that have populations larger than one million people.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The majority of Australia's population lives near coastlines.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Between 1788 and the Second World War, the vast majority of settlers and immigrants came from the British Isles (principally England, Ireland and Scotland), although Australia had significant immigration from China and Germany during the 19th century.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Following Federation in 1901, the white Australia policy was strengthened, restricting further migration from these areas.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] However, this policy was relaxed following WW2, and in the decades following, Australia received a large wave of immigration from across Europe, with many more immigrants arriving from Southern and Eastern Europe than in previous decades.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Following the end of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia adopted multiculturalism as policy, culminating in the Racial Discrimination Act 1975.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Subsequently, there has been a large and continuing wave of immigration from across the world, with Asia being the largest source of immigrants in the 21st century.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Today, Australia has the world's eighth-largest immigrant population, with immigrants accounting for 30% of the population, the highest proportion among major Western nations.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] In 2022–23, 212,789 permanent migrants were admitted to Australia, with a net migration population gain of 518,000 people inclusive of non-permanent residents.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Most entered on skilled visas, however the immigration program also offers visas for family members and refugees.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The Australian Bureau of Statistics asks each Australian resident to nominate up to two ancestries each census and the responses are classified into broad ancestry groups.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 3.8% of the Australian population identified as being Indigenous – Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] English has no legal status in Australia but it is the *de facto* official and national language due to its widespread established use.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australian English is a major variety of the language with a distinctive accent and lexicon, and differs slightly from other varieties of English in grammar and spelling.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] General Australian serves as the standard dialect.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The Australian sign language known as Auslan was used at home by 16,242 people at the time of the 2021 census.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, English was the only language spoken in the home for 72% of the population.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The next most common languages spoken at home were Mandarin (2.7%), Arabic (1.4%), Vietnamese (1.3%), Cantonese (1.2%) and Punjabi (0.9%).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] More than 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018–19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use were endangered.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians – Yumplatok (Torres Strait Creole), Djambarrpuyngu (a Yolŋu language) and Pitjantjatjara (a Western Desert language) were among the most widely spoken.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australia has no state religion; section 116 of the Australian Constitution prohibits federal legislation that would establish any religion, impose any religious observance, or prohibit the free exercise of any religion.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] However, the states still retain the power to pass religiously discriminatory laws.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 38.9% of the population identified as having no religion, up from 15.5% in 2001.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The largest religion is Christianity (43.9% of the population).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The largest Christian denominations are the Catholic Church (20% of the population) and the Anglican Church of Australia (9.8%).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Non-British immigration since the Second World War has led to the growth of non-Christian religions, the largest of which are Islam (3.2%), Hinduism (2.7%), Buddhism (2.4%), Sikhism (0.8%), and Judaism (0.4%).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] In 2021, just under 8,000 people declared an affiliation with traditional Aboriginal religions.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] In Australian Aboriginal mythology and the animist framework developed in Aboriginal Australia, the Dreaming is a sacred era in which ancestral totemic spirit beings formed The Creation.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The Dreaming established the laws and structures of society and the ceremonies performed to ensure continuity of life and land.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australia's life expectancy of 83 years (81 years for males and 85 years for females) is the fifth-highest in the world.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] It has the highest rate of skin cancer in the world, while cigarette smoking is the largest preventable cause of death and disease, responsible for 7.8% of the total mortality and disease.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Ranked second in preventable causes is hypertension at 7.6%, with obesity third at 7.5%.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australia ranked 35th in the world in 2012 for its proportion of obese women and near the top of developed nations for its proportion of obese adults; 63% of its adult population is either overweight or obese.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australia spent about 9.91% of its total GDP to health care in 2021.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] It introduced a national insurance scheme in 1975.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Following a period in which access to the scheme was restricted, the scheme became universal once more in 1981 under the name of Medicare.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The program is nominally funded by an income tax surcharge known as the Medicare levy, currently at 2%.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The states manage hospitals and attached outpatient services, while the Commonwealth funds the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (subsidising the costs of medicines) and general practice.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] School attendance, or registration for home schooling, is compulsory throughout Australia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Education is primarily the responsibility of the individual states and territories; however, the Commonwealth has significant influence through funding agreements.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Since 2014, a national curriculum developed by the Commonwealth has been implemented by the states and territories.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Attendance rules vary between states, but in general children are required to attend school from the age of about 5 until about 16.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] In some states (Western Australia, Northern Territory and New South Wales), children aged 16–17 are required to either attend school or participate in vocational training, such as an apprenticeship.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] According to the 2022 PISA evaluations, Australian 15-year-olds ranked ninth in the OECD for reading and science and tenth for maths.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] However, less than 60% of Australian students achieved the National Proficiency Standard – 51% in maths, 58% in science and 57% in reading.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australia has an adult literacy rate that was estimated to be 99% in 2003.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] However, a 2011–2012 report for the Australian Bureau of Statistics found that 44% of the population does not have high literary and numeracy competence levels, interpreted by others as suggesting that they do not have the "skills needed for everyday life".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australia has 37 government-funded universities and three private universities, as well as a number of other specialist institutions that provide approved courses at the higher education level.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The OECD places Australia among the most expensive nations to attend university.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] There is a state-based system of vocational training, known as TAFE, and many trades conduct apprenticeships for training new tradespeople.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] About 58% of Australians aged from 25 to 64 have vocational or tertiary qualifications and the tertiary graduation rate of 49% is the highest among OECD countries.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] 38% of Australia's population has attained a higher education qualification, which is among the highest percentages in the world.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australia has the highest ratio of international students per head of population in the world by a large margin, with 812,000 international students enrolled in the nation's universities and vocational institutions in 2019.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Accordingly, in 2019, international students represented on average 26.7% of the student bodies of Australian universities.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] International education therefore represents one of the country's largest exports and has a pronounced influence on the country's demographics, with a significant proportion of international students remaining in Australia after graduation on various skill and employment visas.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Education is Australia's third-largest export, after iron ore and coal, and contributed more than $28 billion to the economy in the 2016–17 financial year.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Contemporary Australian culture is diverse and reflects the country's Indigenous traditions, British and Irish heritage, and post-1945 history of multicultural immigration.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The culture of the United States has also been influential.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The evolution of Australian culture since British colonisation has given rise to distinctive cultural traits.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Many Australians identify egalitarianism, mateship, irreverence and a lack of formality as part of their national identity.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] These find expression in Australian slang, as well as Australian humour, which is often characterised as dry, irreverent and ironic.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] What these values mean, and whether Australians uphold them, has been debated since before Federation.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australia has more than 100,000 Aboriginal rock art sites, and traditional designs, patterns and stories infuse contemporary Indigenous Australian art, "the last great art movement of the 20th century" according to critic Robert Hughes; its exponents include Emily Kame Kngwarreye.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Early colonial artists showed a fascination with the unfamiliar land.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The impressionistic works of Arthur Streeton, Tom Roberts and other members of the 19th-century Heidelberg School – the first "distinctively Australian" movement in Western art – gave expression to nationalist sentiments in the lead-up to Federation.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] While the school remained influential into the 1900s, modernists such as Margaret Preston and Clarice Beckett, and, later, Sidney Nolan, explored new artistic trends.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The landscape remained central to the work of Aboriginal watercolourist Albert Namatjira, as well as Fred Williams, Brett Whiteley and other post-war artists whose works, eclectic in style yet uniquely Australian, moved between the figurative and the abstract.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australian literature grew slowly in the decades following European settlement though Indigenous oral traditions, many of which have since been recorded in writing, are much older.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] In the 19th century, Henry Lawson and Banjo Paterson captured the experience of the bush using a distinctive Australian vocabulary.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Their works are still popular; Paterson's bush poem "Waltzing Matilda" (1895) is regarded as Australia's unofficial national anthem.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Miles Franklin is the namesake of Australia's most prestigious literary prize, awarded annually to the best novel about Australian life.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Its first recipient, Patrick White, went on to win the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1973.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australian Booker Prize winners include Peter Carey, Thomas Keneally and Richard Flanagan.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australian public intellectuals have also written seminal works in their respective fields, including feminist Germaine Greer and philosopher Peter Singer.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] In the performing arts, Aboriginal peoples have traditions of religious and secular song, dance and rhythmic music often performed in corroborees.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, Nellie Melba was one of the world's leading opera singers, and later popular music acts such as the Bee Gees, AC/DC, INXS and Kylie Minogue achieved international recognition.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Many of Australia's performing arts companies receive funding through the Australian government's Australia Council.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] There is a symphony orchestra in each state, and a national opera company, Opera Australia, well known for its famous soprano Joan Sutherland.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Ballet and dance are represented by The Australian Ballet and various state companies.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Each state has a publicly funded theatre company.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australia has two public broadcasters (the Australian Broadcasting Corporation and the multicultural Special Broadcasting Service), three commercial television networks, several pay-TV services, and numerous public, non-profit television and radio stations.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Each major city has at least one daily newspaper, and there are two national daily newspapers, *The Australian* and *The Australian Financial Review*.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] In 2024, Reporters Without Borders placed Australia 39th on a list of 180 countries ranked by press freedom, behind New Zealand (19th) and the United Kingdom (23rd), but ahead of the United States (55th).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] This relatively low ranking is primarily because of the limited diversity of commercial media ownership in Australia; most print media are under the control of News Corp Australia (59%) and Nine Entertainment (23%).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Most Indigenous Australian groups subsisted on a diet of native fauna and flora, otherwise called bush tucker.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] It has increased in popularity among non-Indigenous Australians since the 1970s, with examples such as lemon myrtle, the macadamia nut and kangaroo meat now widely available.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The first colonists introduced British and Irish cuisine to the continent.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] This influence is seen in dishes such as fish and chips, and in the Australian meat pie, which is related to the British steak pie.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Also during the colonial period, Chinese migrants paved the way for a distinctive Australian Chinese cuisine.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Post-war migrants transformed Australian cuisine, bringing with them their culinary traditions and contributing to new fusion dishes.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Italians introduced espresso coffee and, along with Greeks, helped develop Australia's café culture, of which the flat white and avocado toast are now considered Australian staples.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Pavlovas, lamingtons, Vegemite and Anzac biscuits are also often called iconic Australian foods.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australia is a leading exporter and consumer of wine.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australian wine is produced mainly in the southern, cooler parts of the country.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The nation also ranks highly in beer consumption, with each state and territory hosting numerous breweries.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The most popular sports in Australia by adult participation are: swimming, athletics, cycling, soccer, golf, tennis, basketball, surfing, netball and cricket.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australia is one of five nations to have participated in every Summer Olympics of the modern era, and has hosted the Games twice: 1956 in Melbourne and 2000 in Sydney.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] It is also set to host the 2032 Games in Brisbane.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australia has also participated in every Commonwealth Games, hosting the event in 1938, 1962, 1982, 2006 and 2018.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The Australian national cricket team competed against England in both the first Test match (1877) and the first One Day International (1971), and against New Zealand in the first Twenty20 International (2004), winning all three games.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] It has also won the men's Cricket World Cup a record six times.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Australia has professional leagues for four football codes, whose relative popularity is divided geographically.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Originating in Melbourne in the 1850s, Australian rules football attracts the most television viewers in all states except New South Wales and Queensland, where rugby league holds sway, followed by rugby union.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] Soccer, while ranked fourth in television viewers and resources, has the highest overall participation rates.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The surf lifesaving movement originated in Australia in the early 20th century, following the relaxation of laws prohibiting daylight bathing on Australian beaches.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/australia-p02] The volunteer lifesaver is one of the country's icons.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] The bandicoots are members of the order Peramelemorphia and the word bandicoot is often used informally to refer to any peramelemorph, such as the bilby.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] The term originally referred to the unrelated Indian bandicoot rat from the Telugu word *pandikokku* (పందికొక్కు), wherein *pandi* means pig and *kokku* means rat.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] Bandicoots have V-shaped faces, ending with their prominent noses similar to proboscides.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] These noses make them, along with bilbies, similar in appearance to elephant shrews and extinct leptictids and they are distantly related to both mammal groups.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] With their well-attuned snouts and sharp claws, bandicoots are fossorial diggers.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] They have small but fine teeth that allow them to chew their food easily.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] Like most marsupials, male bandicoots have bifurcated penises.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] The embryos of bandicoots have a chorioallantoic placenta that connects them to the uterine wall, in addition to the choriovitelline placenta common to all marsupials.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] However the chorioallantoic placenta is small compared with those of the Placentalia and lacks chorionic villi.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] Bandicoots can reach 11 to 31 in (28 to 79 cm) in length and 0.4 to 3.5 lb (0.18 to 1.6 kg) in weight.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] A bandicoot has a long pointed snout, large ears, a short body and a long tail.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] Its body is covered with fur that can be brown, black, golden, white or grey.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] Bandicoots have strong hind legs well adapted for jumping.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] Bandicoots also have low body temperatures and low basal metabolic rates, which aids their survival in hot and dry climates.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] They also have a low total water evaporative rate and effective panting mechanisms, which further aid their survival in hotter temperatures.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] Classification within the Peramelemorphia was previously thought to be straightforward, with two families in the order—the short-legged and mostly herbivorous bandicoots, and the longer-legged, nearly carnivorous bilbies.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] In recent years, however, the situation clearly has become more complex.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] First, the bandicoots of the New Guinean and far-northern Australian rainforests were deemed distinct from all other bandicoots and were grouped together in the separate family Peroryctidae.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] More recently, the bandicoot families were reunited in the Peramelidae, with the New Guinean species split into four genera in two subfamilies, Peroryctinae and Echymiperinae, while the "true bandicoots" occupy the subfamily Peramelinae.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] The only exception is the now-extinct pig-footed bandicoot, which has been given its own family, Chaeropodidae.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] The name bandicoot is an Anglicised version of a word from the Telugu language of South India meaning 'pig-rat'.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] What are now called bandicoots are not found in India and 'bandicoot' was originally applied to completely unrelated mammals—several species of large rat (rodents).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] Today these species, belonging to the genera *Bandicota* and *Nesokia*, are referred to as bandicoot rats.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] It is known as ***aine*** in the Abinomn language of Papua, Indonesia.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] Bandicoots have different names by the indigenous peoples of the Australia–New Guinea region.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/bandicoot] For example, the Kaurna people refer to the southern brown bandicoot as the *bung* or the *marti*.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] The arrival of Europeans in Australia has brought new ecological challenges.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] European colonisation of Australia has directly affected *Banksia* through deforestation, exploitation of flowers and changes to the fire regime.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] In addition, the accidental introduction and spread of plant pathogens such as *Phytophthora cinnamomi* (dieback) pose a serious threat to the genus' habitat and biodiversity.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Various conservation measures have been put in place to mitigate these threats, but a number of taxa remain endangered.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] The pollination ecology of *Banksia* has been well studied, because the large showy inflorescences make it easy to conduct pollination experiments, and the pollination roles of nectariferous birds and mammals makes the genus a popular subject for zoologists.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Visits to *Banksia* inflorescences by western honeybees and nectarivorous birds are often observed and are obviously important to pollination.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Also important are visits by nectariferous mammals, although such visits are rarely observed because these mammals are usually nocturnal and reclusive.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Studies have found that *Banksia* inflorescences are foraged by a variety of small mammals, including marsupials (such as honey possums and yellow-footed antechinus, *Antechinus flavipes*), and rodents (such as the pale field rat, *Rattus tunneyi*).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Studies in New South Wales and in Western Australia found that small mammals can carry pollen loads comparable to those of nectarivorous birds, likely making them effective pollinators of many "Banksia" species.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Almost all *Banksia* species studied so far have shown outcrossing rates among the highest ever recorded for plants; that is, very few *Banksia* plants are found to occur as a result of self-fertilisation.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] There are a number of potential reasons for this.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] One possibility is that *Banksia* flowers are simply not exposed to their own pollen.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] This is highly unlikely for two reasons.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Firstly, the morphology of the *Banksia* flower makes it virtually inevitable that the stigma will be exposed to its own pollen, since it functions also as a "pollen-presenter".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] It has been suggested that this problem would be avoided if the flowers were strongly protandrous, but the evidence so far supports only partial protandry.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Moreover, the question of protandry of individual flowers is probably irrelevant, because the sequential anthesis of flowers means that each inflorescence will typically contain flowers in both male and female stages at the same time.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Observations of foraging patterns in pollinators have shown that transfer of pollen between different flowers in the same inflorescence is inevitable.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Another possibility is that the high outcrossing rate is due to self-incompatibility, due either to a failure to fertilise or abortion of self-fertilised fruit.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Studies have shown self-compatibility of pollen to vary between *Banksia* species, with some but not all species inhibiting the growth of pollen tubes for pollen from its own flowers.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] A more likely form of self-incompatibility is the spontaneous abortion of fruits that have been self-fertilised.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] These could be caused either by the expression of lethal genes, or the expression of genes that, while not lethal, cause the maternal plant to abort.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Genetic causes are thought to be a common form of self-incompatibility, because of the high genetic load of the genus.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] However abortion rates are difficult to assess because the ovaries are deeply embedded in the "rhachis" (woody spine) of the inflorescence.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Finally, there is the mechanism of "facultative" abortion of fruits, where a maternal plant without the resources to mature all fruit aborts the least vigorous ones.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] This is thought to be common in those taxa that are generally self-compatible, since even these have high outcrossing rates.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] For example, *B. neoanglica*, one of the most self-compatible *Banksia* species, has been shown to set far more cross-pollinated than self-pollinated fruit.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] A few species, such as *B. brownii*, are exceptional in having low outcrossing rates.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] In all cases these are rare species that occur in very small populations, which increases the probability of self-fertilisation, and may discourage visits by pollinators.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] All *Banksia* exhibit serotiny to some extent.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Most retain all of their seed until release is triggered by fire, but a few species release a small amount of seed spontaneously.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Serotiny is achieved through the mechanism of thick, woody follicles, which are held tightly closed by resin.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Seeds retained in follicles are protected from granivores and the heat of bushfire, and remain viable for around ten years.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Follicles require a critical heat to melt the resin, so that the follicles may begin opening; for *B. elegans*, for example, this is 2 minutes at 500 °C.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Those species with high heat requirements typically retain their old withered florets.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] These are highly combustible and thus help ensure the critical heat is reached.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] With some exceptions, each follicle contains two seeds plus a winged "separator".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] While the separator remains in the follicle, it holds the seeds in position.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] In some species, the separator remains in the follicle until it has cooled; once cooled, the separator loosens and falls out, and the seeds follow.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] In this way the separator ensures that the seeds fall onto cool ground.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] In other species, the separator does not loosen until it has been wet.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] In these species, the seeds do not fall to the ground until the first rains after the bushfire.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Seed is typically released over a period of about 90 days.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Immediately after bushfire, granivorous birds move in to extract seed from newly open follicles, and to eat seeds that have fallen to the ground.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Those seeds that escape the granivores are soon buried by wind and surface water.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Most *Banksia* seedlings do not survive to adulthood.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] A major reason for this is a lack of water.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Competition for soil moisture can be intense, especially during drought.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] In one study, an estimated 13680 seedlings were counted over June–October following an experimental bushfire, but by January only eleven plants remained.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Other threats to seedling establishment include predation by invertebrates such as grasshoppers and mites; and by vertebrates such as kangaroos and bandicoots.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Banksia seed is predated on by birds and insects.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Insects also feed on stems, leaves, flowers and cones.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Many species of fungi live on *Banksia* plants, including *Banksiamyces*.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Most *Banksia* species are highly susceptible to *Phytophthora cinnamomi* dieback.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] The biodiversity of *Banksia* is impacted by a range of processes.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Major threats include disease, changes in fire frequency and intensity, clearing of land for agriculture, mining, urban development and roads and exploitation of flowers, seeds and foliage by the cut flower and other industries.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Three *Banksia* species are currently declared endangered under Australia's Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999, and a further two are considered vulnerable.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] The most severe disease threat to *Banksia* is the introduced plant pathogen *Phytophthora cinnamomi*, commonly known as "dieback".
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] This is a water mould that attacks the roots of plants, destroying the structure of the root tissues, "rotting" the root, and preventing the plant from absorbing water and nutrients.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] *Banksia'*s proteoid roots make it highly susceptible to this disease, with infected plants typically dying within a few years of exposure.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] The threat of exposure to dieback is greatest in southwest Western Australia, where dieback infestation has reached epidemic proportions.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] This area holds the greatest species diversity for *Banksia*, with all species considered susceptible to infection.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Consequently, a number of southwestern species are considered under threat from dieback.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Nearly every known wild population of *B. brownii* shows some signs of dieback infection, and it is said that this species would be extinct within a decade if it were not protected.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Other vulnerable species include *B. cuneata*, *B. goodii*, *B. oligantha* and *B. verticillata*.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Infested areas of *Banksia* forest in southwest Western Australia typically have less than 30% of the cover of uninfested areas.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Plant deaths in such large proportions can have a profound influence on the makeup of plant communities.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] For example, in southwestern Australia *Banksia* often occurs as an understory to forests of jarrah (*Eucalyptus marginata*), another species highly vulnerable to dieback.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Infestation kills both the jarrah overstory and the *Banksia* understory, and over time these may be replaced by a more open woodland consisting of an overstory of the resistant marri (*Corymbia calophylla*), and an understory of the somewhat resistant Parrotbush (*Dryandra sessilis*).
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Dieback is notoriously difficult to manage.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] A number of protective measures have been implemented to slow the spread of disease and boost the survival rates of infected plants; these include restricting access to infected and susceptible sites, the collection and cold-storage of seed, and the treatment of plants with phosphite.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Phosphite boosts the resistance of both infected and uninfected plants, and also acts as a direct fungicide.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Aerial spraying of phosphite boosts plant survival and slows the spread of infection, but must be carefully managed as studies have shown that foliar spraying of phosphite adversely affects root and shoot growth.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Direct injection of phosphite into tree stems appears to lack this disadvantage, but is costly to administer and restricted to known plants.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Because dieback thrives in moist soil conditions, it can be a severe problem for *Banksia*s that are watered, such as in the cut flower industry and urban gardens.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] In some species this problem can be countered by grafting onto a rootstock of an eastern species, many of which demonstrate at least some resistant to dieback.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Other diseases to which *Banksia* species are vulnerable include the aerial canker fungus *Zythiostroma* and the parasitic fungus *Armillaria*.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] The frequency and intensity of bushfires are important factors in the population health of *Banksia*s.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] The ideal time interval between bushfires varies from species to species, but twenty years is a typical figure.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] If bushfires occur too frequently, plants are killed before they reach fruiting age or before they have developed a substantial seed bank.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] This can seriously reduce or even eliminate populations in some areas.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Longer time intervals also reduce populations, as more plants die of natural attrition between fires.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Unlike some other Proteaceae, *Banksia*s do not release their seed when they die, and dead plants usually release much less seed in response to fire than live plants do, so long fire intervals cause seed wastage.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] If a fire is not intense enough to promote the release of seed, then the effective interval between seed release will be further increased by the loss of fire fuel.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Fire intervals are not as critical for resprouters, as adults typically survive fire.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Fire does kill seedlings, however, as most resprouters do not develop a lignotuber until they reach fruiting age.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Thus overly frequent fires prevent the recruitment of new adults, and populations decline at the rate that adults die.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] It is widely accepted that colonisation by Europeans has led to an increase in fire frequency.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] This is especially the case near urban areas, where bushland is subject to both arson and prescribed burns.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] The proximity of urban areas creates a need to manage the ferocity and rate of occurrence of bushfires, resulting in pressure to prescribe regular low-intensity burns.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] This is at odds with the conservation needs of *Banksia*, which requires intense fires at long intervals.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] The distribution of *Banksia* habitat coincides with areas of high population density, and large areas of *Banksia* woodland have been cleared for agriculture, mining, urban development and roads.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] As well as the direct loss of population and habitat, this has led to an increased spread of weeds and disease.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] As *Banksia* occurs on the poorest soils, the areas in which they are most abundant have been the last to be cleared for agriculture.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Nonetheless, it is estimated that 55% of Banksia woodland had been cleared by 1986.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Species threatened by clearing include *B. hookeriana* and the endangered species *B. cuneata* and *B. goodii*.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] 19 *Banksia* taxa are currently declared rare.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] Protection is afforded to them under the Australian Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999 (EPBC Act), and the Western Australian Wildlife Conservation Act 1950.
[src:ecology-of-banksia/ecology-of-banksia] The Department of Environment and Conservation also provides for taxa to be declared "Priority Flora", either because they are poorly known, or because they are rare but not threatened.
